<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq's 8th National Census Starts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's eighth national census,
the first one since the U.N. imposed embargo against the country
for its invasion of Kuwait in 1990, started today.
</P>
<P>
About 159,500 government officials went door-to-door to help
fill in the census forms distributed to urban and rural areas
throughout the country to ensure it a success, an official from
Iraq's High General Census Committee told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The official, who declined to be named, said the committee,
which oversees the census, is headed by Ezzat Ibrahim, vice
chairman of the Iraqi Revolutionary Command Council.
</P>
<P>
The census is reportedly to cover, in addition to population,
property estate, crops, the social status of Iraqis and the
distribution of man power according to age. Iraqis residing
overseas will also be included.
</P>
<P>
The results will be released Friday. They may give some clue to
the toll taken by Iraq's war with Iran during 1980-88 and the 1991
Gulf War. The census is also expected to reveal the economic
situation of the Iraqi people living under U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Iraq never disclosed the number of people killed during the
Iraq-Iran war but the casualties were estimated at 1 million. But
it claimed the U.N.-imposed sanctions since 1991 have caused
hundreds of thousands of Iraqis, mainly children and the diseased,
to die due to the lack of food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
Traffic and travel were forbidden completely from 4:00 a.m. up
to 8:00 p.m. local time (0010-1700 GMT) today to facilitate the
census.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's first census was conducted in 1927 when the population
was recorded at 2,968,754, and the last one, in 1987 when the
country's population reached 16,278,316.
</P>
<P>
The country's population is estimated to have increased to more
than 22 million now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
