<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1530 GMT, October 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO -- A more prosperous Hong Kong with sustainable economic
growth and an unchanged life style is emerging, said Tung Chee
Hwa, chief executive of China's Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
Speaking today at a reception in his honor by Chinese
Ambassador to Japan Xu Dunxin, Tung said he made the statement
because every element for Hong Kong's success had been ensured
under the "Basic Law" and "one country, two systems"
principle. (Tung-Japan-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea's ruling New Korea Party (NKP) today filed
with prosecutors allegations of bribery, tax evasion and libel
against opposition leader Kim Dae-jung.
</P>
<P>
The NKP also handed the prosecution "concrete evidence" to back
its claims of corruption against Kim, the leader of the main
opposition National Congress for New Politics (NCNP).
</P>
<P>
The NKP charged that Kim had taken illegal bribes amounting to
more than 13 billion won (about 15 million U.S. dollars) from 10
business groups and had evaded taxes by stashing over 100 billion
won (about 110 million U.S. dollars) in secret funds kept in the
bank accounts of relatives and in-laws. (SKorea-Ruling Party)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PYONGYANG -- The United States decided on Tuesday to provide 50
million U.S. dollars worth of medical aid to the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), the Korean Central News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The emergency aid includes preventive injections for measles
and comprehensive instruments for treatment of the common cold.
</P>
<P>
This is the fourth batch of humanitarian aid from the U.S.,
which has also given a total of 52 million dollars worth of food
aid to the DPRK in three batches, the report said.(DPRK-US-Aid)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- The Italian government won a confidence vote in the
lower house this afternoon, restoring its majority and formally
ending the political crisis triggered by the resignation of Prime
Minister Romano Prodi a week ago.
</P>
<P>
Prodi announced his resignation on October 9, following the
Communist Refoundation Party's refusal to soften its opposition to
rewriting the deficit-cutting draft. Prodi's government depended
on the Communist Refoundation Party in the lower house to pass
legislation. (Italy-Government-Vote) 
</P>
</TEXT>
