<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea May Talk Business With DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 16 (Xinhua) -- South Korea will contact the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) if Pyongyang proposes
a dialogue on economic cooperation, a high-ranking official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
The official was quoted by Yonhap News Agency as saying:
"Following Kim Jong-il's formal taking over the leadership of the
Worker's Party, it is possible that some changes take place in the
economic area in North Korea (DPRK)."
</P>
<P>
According to the South-North basic agreements signed in early
1990s by the two sides, Pyongyang and Seoul can begin economic
cooperation with each other at any time, the official added.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government has permitted some private
businesses to enter the DPRK for economic cooperation, but
economic cooperation between the two governments has not yet
begun. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
