<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen Orders Security Review After Weapons Stolen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen has ordered a military-wide security review
following the arrests of 14 people, including six Marines,
suspected of steal military weapons.
</P>
<P>
"It is imperative that we be confident that military arms and
munitions are tightly controlled and safeguarded," Cohen said in
ordering the 30-day review.
</P>
<P>
The arrests on Thursday were part of an ongoing 18-month
investigation into the theft of military weapons, including rocket
launchers, machine guns, mines, mortars and grenades.
</P>
<P>
Much of the ordnance was stolen from Camp Lejeune, the
sprawling Marine base in eastern North Carolina where five of the
Marines were arrested.
</P>
<P>
The sixth Marine, Capt. Thomas Crawford, was arrested in
Millis, Massachusetts, about 30 miles southwest of Boston.
Crawford recently transferred from Camp Lejeune to the Naval
Marine Corps Reserve Center in Worcester, Massachusetts, according
to Marine officials.
</P>
<P>
Charges were pending against the Marines. The eight civilians
were arrested and charged with a variety of federal crimes for
allegedly manufacturing and selling military explosives and
hardware. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
