<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Runner Sets Asian Record at National Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 17 (Xinhua) -- One Asian record was shattered
on the opening day of the athletics competition at the Chinese
Eighth National Games here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Li Xuemei from Southwest China's Sichuan Province clocked 10.90
seconds in the women's 100 meters heat to shave 0.12 second off
the listed Aisan record. The old mark was established by Liu
Xiaomei of China in Beijing four years ago. The finals will be
held on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Li jumped into the lead after 50 meters and she
apparently slowed down about five meters to go with others
struggling far behind her.
</P>
<P>
"She performed well," said her trainer Lin Gang, "We hadn't
expected her to break the record. I think she also has the
possibility to improve the Asian mark in her specialty -- 200
meters."
</P>
<P>
Li, who competed in the world championships last August,
equalled the Asian record in the 200 meters by timing 22.39
seconds in Athens, Greece.
</P>
<P>
Middle and long distance runners from Northeast China's
Liaoning Province dominated the men's and women's 1500 meters
heats with "Ma's Family Army" setting the pace.
</P>
<P>
Song Weizeng, who is under the guidance of coach Ma Junren,
clocked three minutes and 40.23 seconds in the 1500 meters heat to
beat the national mark of 3:40.93. All the top five finishers,
three from Ma's team, also surpassed the national record.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 1500 meters heat, eight Liaoning runners
qualified for the finals, the other four finalists are from Henan
and Jiangsu Provinces.
</P>
<P>
After today's competition, Chinese track and field circles
predicted that Ma's team would make another haul of golds after
four years. At the Seventh National Games in 1993 in Beijing, Ma's
team set three world records.
</P>
<P>
"Ma Junren will make another surprise in the track," said Du
Huaice, coach of Henan team, "let's wait and see."
</P>
<P>
Olympic champion Wang Junxia did not compete in the race as she
just resumed training in August. However, she came to Shanghai to
watch the Games and she said she was preparing for the Sydney
Olympics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
