<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fund-Raising: Something New for China's State-owned Enterprises (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese economists say that
state-owned enterprises need a more open environment and more
international capital to transform them.
</P>
<P>
A large number of large and medium-sized state-owned
enterprises have applied for listing on markets to get more
development funds, and many smaller ones are using a joint stock
partnership system.
</P>
<P>
Chinese now have more than four trillion yuan in capital that
could be channeled into different sectors. One economist has
predicted that the reorganization of state-owned enterprises will
need two or three trillion yuan, so the ordinary Chinese could be
significant in this.
</P>
<P>
A securities investment fund is the preferred form of
investment for many ordinary Chinese.
</P>
<P>
The State Council has approved some temporary securities
investment fund measures to keep it fair.
</P>
<P>
Guo Shuqing, the secretary-general of the State Commission for
Restructuring the Economy, says that China will open more channels
for raising funds in future, like investment funds, special
project investment, listing shares abroad, or bank loans.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Dongsheng, deputy director of the State Planning
Commission's finance department says that one way is to issue
convertible bonds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fund-Raising: Something New for China's State-owned Enterprises (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Only companies that are listed on the stock market can issue
convertible bonds. But China has 700 listed companies only, Zhang
notes. So, issuing convertible bonds by companies that are not
listed is compatible with China's condition, he said.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, China's largest industrial center, has made some
progress in opening up more investment channels. It plans to raise
10 billion yuan on the stock market, each year, for the next few
years, a municipal government official says.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, some non-banking financial institutions have
gotten involved in banking transactions on a trial basis. The
emergence of more investment banks will lead to more competition
and integration of financial capital and industrial capital.
</P>
<P>
The formation of a capital market and the convergence of
China's practices and those of the international capital market
provide an opportunity to develop an investment banking system,
says Gao Shangquan, a noted economist.
</P>
<P>
He call for importing more foreign funds, establishing
Sino-foreign investment organizations, and training a contingent
of high-level managers.
</P>
<P>
The Shenzhen Property Rights Agency has formed ties with
investment banks, financial consortia, and investment funds in the
United States, Japan, Britain, Australia and Hong Kong and has had
some good results. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
