<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Baby Born from Frozen Eggs in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 17 (Xinhua) -- A 39-year-old Georgia women
gave birth to twin boys after being implanted with another women's
eggs that had been frozen two years earlier, researchers at a
private clinic in Atlanta said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It was the first successful pregnancy in the United States
using an egg that had been frozen and it promises to make it
vastly easier for older women to remain fertile.
</P>
<P>
The consequence would be to allow women to freeze their eggs
when they are young, for use later when they are older and their
eggs are of poorer quality. It would make menopause obsolete, in
effect, because women could have their own babies, with eggs they
stored when they were younger, at any time in life.
</P>
<P>
It would also enable women who are undergoing chemotherapy,
which can damage the ovaries, to save their eggs for later use.
</P>
<P>
Researchers from the Reproductive Biology Associates said the
frozen eggs were from a 29-year-old women and they had been frozen
for 25 months before they were fertilized.
</P>
<P>
The same clinic in 1993 produced the first U.S. baby using
sperm injected directly into a woman's egg.
</P>
<P>
Until now, U.S. doctors have been able to produce pregnancies
from frozen embryos -- eggs fertilized with sperm and then frozen
-- but eggs alone proved too fragile.
</P>
<P>
In 1986, a doctor in Australia was able to produce the first
known births from frozen eggs. A year later, a team of German
doctors also produced frozen-egg pregnancies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Housing Construction Up Sharply in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Construction starts of new
homes in the U.S. jumped by 7.9 percent last month, the sharpest
increase in seven months, U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that the U.S. housing starts increased to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.5 million in September
following drops of 5.1 percent in August and 2.5 percent in July.
</P>
<P>
The construction of single-family homes rose by 6.9 percent in
the month to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.17 million.
Construction of apartments also jumped by 11.5 percent to an
annual rate of 330,000.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, the housing starts increased in all areas in
September. Starts rose by 10.7 percent in the West, the largest
gain since January. They increased by 9.7 percent in the
Northeast, 9.3 percent in the Midwest and 5.6 percent in the
South.
</P>
<P>
In the first nine months of this year, the housing starts in
the U.S. are running 2.2 percent below last year.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that applications for building permits --
a barometer of future building plans -- also rose in all regions.
They were up 3.4 percent nationally to a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 1.45 million.
</P>
<P>
U.S. economists said that the larger increase in September
doesn't changed their view that housing construction won't quite
match last year's eight-year high of 1.48 million but remain
strong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strong Pound Hits UK Export Orders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 17 (Xinhua) -- British manufacturing has been
dealt a heavy blow by the strength of the pound with export orders
now at their lowest level for six years, the latest quarterly
survey of business by the British Chambers of Commerce (BCC)
showed today.
</P>
<P>
The survey of 8,000 companies found that for the first time in
five years, the majority of firms are reporting falling export
sales and orders, which are at their lowest level since 1991. The
situation will not likely to improve in the short term.
</P>
<P>
The BCC blamed the sharp rise in the value of the pound since
last year for the fall in exports, saying that businesses were
losing out to foreign competition at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, businesses pleaded for relief from the Bank of
England in the form of no more increase in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
"We don't want to see further increase in interest rates which
would fuel further rises in sterling," said Ian Peters, deputy
director-general of the BCC.
</P>
<P>
The survey also highlighted the growing disparity between gloom
among manufacturing firms and the bouyant state of the service
sector, which reported the highest levels of optimism since the
late 1980s and record levels of investment and employment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
