<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB President Stresses Poverty Eradication in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- World Bank President James D.
Wolfensohn today called for more efforts in poverty eradication
and offered more money in this field in Bangladesh, one of the
world's poorest and most densely populated countries.
</P>
<P>
"Bangladesh has no reason not to win its battle against poverty
and social injustice. You can count on the continued and growing
support of the World Bank Group in this endeavor," he told a press
conference held here today.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn, who came Monday on his first official visit here,
has agreed to commit upwards of 500 million US dollars annually,
instead of about 300 million dollars in recent years, in
interest-free credits, in the coming five years to support a
strong macro-economic and structural reform program.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh is one of the largest borrowers from the
International Development Association (IDA), which provides
interest-free credits to poor countries. Dhaka has got over 7.5
billion U.S. dollar commitment in IDA credits since its
independence in 1971.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn told the reporters that he was deeply impressed by
the strength and courage of the villagers he met and the progress
made by some non-government organizations in fighting poverty in
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Wolfensohn met with political leaders,
representatives of civil society and the business community. He
also visited World Bank-supported and other development projects
in action.
</P>
<P>
Mentioning his talks with Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina,
Wolfensohn said that they agreed that the IDA assistance should
place special emphasis on supporting expanded human resource
development, especially education and nutrition, and promoting the
equality of women.
</P>
<P>
The bank chief also stressed the importance of developing
long-term programs for improved infrastructure and water resource
management, the necessity of strengthening the financial system,
and the importance of private sector development.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank president is scheduled to leave here tomorrow
morning for a visit to Pakistan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Announce New Investment Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Commerce Minister
Ishaq Dar said today the country will announce a new investment
policy for the current fiscal year by the end of October.
</P>
<P>
Dar disclosed this at the inauguration of the 4th Pakistan
International Footwear Exhibition here.
</P>
<P>
He said the new policy aimed to spur the country's economy and
to increase the country's exports to the world market.
</P>
<P>
As for the current devaluation of Pakistan's currency, the
rupee, Dar said it was no real devaluation but merely a long-due
readjustment of the rupee against a couple of other currencies.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the readjustment was necessary to retain
Pakistan's overseas markets as some of its competitors have
devalued their currencies, making the rupee overvalued with regard
to exports.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the readjustment will help his country achieve
the export target of 9.5 billion U.S. dollars for this fiscal
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
