<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Australian sharemarket closed
down today under the impact of Wall Street fall, but the bank
stocks were pushed back by a strong bond market.
</P>
<P>
"Bonds were better all day long and that's what fed over into
equities. Obviously with bonds there was a positive lead on into
the banks," said Intersuisse equities manager Andrew Sekely.
</P>
<P>
Peter Struk of Reynolds &AMP; Co agreed that the bond market had
helped the equities market, adding that bargain hunters had lifted
the all ordinaries index off its lows in morning trading.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones closed down sharply overnight, falling 119.10
points to 7938.88, on fears that corporate earnings had peaked.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed down 7.4 points at 2645.6,
ranging between a high of 2653.0 and a low of 2635.7.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 292.66 million shares traded and valued
at 851.60 million Australian dollars (625.93 million US dollars).
Falls outnumbered rises by 685 to 444.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index was down 7.5 points at 1292.9 and the
all industrials index was down 7.9 points at 4362.9.
</P>
<P>
Among the resource majors, BHP was down 10.9 cents, Rio Tinto
was down 23 cents and WMC was up seven.
</P>
<P>
The bank index gained 1.10 percent. National Australia Bank
gained 36.6 cents, ANZ Banking Group gained 27, Westpac Banking
Corp was steady and Commonwealth Bank rose two to 16.79 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was down 12.6 points at 1299.4, with Normandy
Mining losing four to 1.78 Australian dollars and Plutonic
Resources dropping 22 to 3.30 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Trading in Sydney gold bullion closed at 324.0 US dollars an
ounce, down 2.05 on the opening price of 326.05 US dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
