<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Provides Academic Exchange Forum At Population Conference (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Today was the last day of the
23rd International Union for Scientific Study of Population
(IUSSP) General Population Conference in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
During the conference, Chinese demographers held discussions
with their foreign counterparts.
</P>
<P>
The conference provided a good opportunity for many people to
understand China's population and demographic research, according
to Prof. Dudley L.Poston of Texas A &AMP; M University.
</P>
<P>
Poston has visited China several times and says he has
witnessed great progress in the country's demographic work in the
past two decades, citing the many academic papers of the younger
generation of Chinese demographers now being published in
international journals.
</P>
<P>
Prof. John Caldwell, president of IUSSP, points out that the
fact of the international conference's being held in China is
itself significant, because, "What happens in China determines
considerablely what happens in the world."
</P>
<P>
Since the mid-1980s, more information about the nation's
population and demographic studies has been made available abroad,
and the seven formal and informal symposia on China at the
conference signified a new level of demographic study.
</P>
<P>
Discussions focused on censuses, statistics, family planning,
population migration and urbanization, aging and old age security,
marriage and the family, population and sustainable development,
women's issues and health issues of women.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Provides Academic Exchange Forum at Population Conference (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Like many developing countries, China faces the problem of a
large population putting pressure on economic development," says
Prof. Jiang Zhenghua, vice-minister of the State Family Planning
Commission.
</P>
<P>
But, the one child policy that took effect in the late 1970s
has helped the country control the fast growth of population,
Jiang notes, and the birth rate dropped to 17 per thousand last
year, from 33 per thousand in 1970.
</P>
<P>
"Many scholars in developing countries have expressed a hope of
visiting China to learn from the Chinese experience," he says, and
the conference and some travelling programs have made that
possible.
</P>
<P>
Foreign researchers have used the conference to understand
China better, and the more than 500 Chinese scholars there also
used the opportunity to make connections with foreign academics.
</P>
<P>
For many Chinese scholars, financial and language problems have
long been obstacles to communications with their foreign
counterparts. But, this conference, the first in China, made
Chinese one of the three working languages so that communication
between the Chinese and foreign scholars would not be such a
problem.
</P>
<P>
What was even more significant about the conference, Jiang
says, was that it will promote demographic research in China, and
the economic construction and opening-up as well.
</P>
<P>
China has placed much more importance on the quality of life
and sustainable development of the economy and society since the
1994 Cairo International Conference on Population and Development,
he explains, and "This conference will help Chinese demographers
and people involved in family planning work to have a better
understanding of those issues."
</P>
<P>
"At the turn of the century, we hope to have more exchanges
with our foreign counterparts in order to find better solutions
for China's population problems," Prof. Peng Xizhe, director of
Fudan University's Institute of Population Research, said at the
closing ceremony today.
</P>
<P>
"We also hope that our research on China's population issues
will make a greater contribution to worldwide demographic
studies," he says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Weaker At Weekend Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
weaker today against its US counterpart, as players squared up
their positions ahead of weekend and expected good inflation news
next week.
</P>
<P>
The consumer price index data due here next Wednesday is
expected to show the inflation rate at levels not seen in nearly
35 years.
</P>
<P>
"There is also some more talk about the possibility of an
easing when the data comes out next week," said a trader at a
domestic bank.
</P>
<P>
"Inflation is likely to have fallen to a 35-year low in the
September quarter," Colonial State Bank chief economist Craig
James said.
</P>
<P>
Colonial State Bank has forecast headline inflation to have
risen by 0.1 percent in the three months to September, for a
year-on-year gain of just 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The currency ended at 73.42 US cents, down from 73.79 US cents
previously.
</P>
<P>
In early dealings today the Australian dollar was buoyed by
reports that the Federal Government could abolish the 9.8 percent
withholding tax levied on offshore holdings of federal and state
government bonds before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The local currency tapped a high of 74 US cents before edging
back in afternoon dealings. The market later sold the currency
lower to its closing levels.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was at 88.46 yen, from 88.82, and at
1.2912 marks, up from 1.2897.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
