<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Opera Festival Curtained Up in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Opera Festival,
the largest of its kind ever held in Hong Kong, was kicked off
tonight with the brilliant performance of Cantonese opera
"Assassination of Emperor Qin" by Hong Kong artists.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day festival presented by the Provisional
Urban Council of Hong Kong, more than 40 Chinese opera troupes
from China's inland and Hong Kong will perform their masterpieces
which vary from the popular Cantonese, Beijing, Sichuan and
Shaoxing operas to the rarely seen Hui, Qin, Han and Jin operas.
</P>
<P>
With Hong Kong's return to the motherland, a tide of fervor for
appreciation and knowledge of Chinese culture could be strongly
felt in every sector of the community, Pao Ping-wing, chairman of
the Council's Culture Select Committee, said at the opening
ceremony this evening.
</P>
<P>
He added that not only does the festival offer a most
penetrative perspective to get to know Chinese culture, it also
offers a rare opportunity for maestros in Hong Kong and the inland
to share their artistic experiences and further promote this
incomparable art form.
</P>
<P>
Chinese opera is a unique performing art with deep cultural
roots and rich folk origins. Its strong presence can also be found
in the theoretical underpinning of Western performing art.
</P>
<P>
Through thousands of years' practice and evolution, Chinese
opera has developed into an artistic gem combining elements of
music, dance, drama, acrobatics, literature, elaborate stage
costumes and symbolic make-up all in a single performance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
