<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Two Dismal Weeks for Australian PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The first half of this month
may have been the most turbulent part in the political life of
Australian Prime Minister John Howard who came to power in March,
1996.
</P>
<P>
Howard's government plunged into a crisis in the past two weeks
over a travel allowance scandal that forced the resignation of
several cabinet ministers and a reshuffle of the cabinet.
The scandal was revealed in late September when former transport
minister John Sharp was forced to resign after being charged with
wrongfully claiming 8,740 Australian dollars (6,292 U.S. dollars)
of travel allowances.
</P>
<P>
The fraud later also forced the resignations of Administrative
Services Minister David Jull and Science Minister Peter McGauran
who were accused of trying to cover up the scandal.
The scandal also cost the political life of Howard's closest and
long-time political ally Grahame Morris, who masterminded his 1996
election victory over the Australian Labor Party.
On September 26, Howard announced that he had sacked his senior
political adviser Morris and office manager Fiona Mckenna. Howard
blamed them for not informing him of the travel allowance fraud.
</P>
<P>
Howard, who was accused by the Labor Party -- the country's
largest opposition party -- of trying to cover the scandal,
suffered another blow as Labor's then deputy senate leader Nick
Sherry shocked the nation by attempting to commit suicide on
October 2.
Sherry was also accused of mistakenly claiming travel allowances
in a tit-for-tat attack from the Howard government.
Howard was forced to announced on October 5 a reshuffle of his
cabinet in an effort to overcome the crisis over the travel
allowance scandal.
</P>
<P>
Howard is also under fire from an influential businessman.
Crown Casino boss Lloyd Williams publicly called for the return
of former prime minister Paul Keating, who lost the 1996 election
to Howard.
Williams has berated the government for being "totally out of
step" with Asia.
</P>
<P>
"I do think that Paul Keating had a wonderful vision for Asia,"
said Williams Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"I only wish Paul Keating was here and he would have got rid of
the Hanson factor...I think she's doing some incredible damage to
us."
</P>
<P>
Independent MP Pauline Hanson and her One Nation Party have
been advocating for a cut in the intake of Asian immigrants and
foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Former PM Malcolm Fraser also criticized Howard for failing to
fight Hanson's divisive policies with sufficient speed or vigor.
This week, another ex-Liberal Party leader John Hewson joined the
fray.
</P>
<P>
Hewson said Howard had failed to effectively tackle the Hanson
threat and it was doing immeasurable damage with Australia's major
trading partners.
</P>
<P>
"Howard played the game to get there but they (the electorate)
didn't expect that when he got to government he'd continue to play
the game," Hewson said.
</P>
<P>
"They'd expected that he would deliver on the (economic) reform
messages that he had been talking about for so many years ... the
government is not delivering," said the ex-Liberal leader.
</P>
<P>
Big business also turned up the heat on Howard, criticizing his
government's piecemeal approach to industry policy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0057 </DOCNO>
