<HEADLINE> Firing Incident Not to Affect Pak-Iranian Ties: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif and visiting Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister Mohsin
Aminzada today reaffirmed that the recent killing of five Iranians
in Pakistan would not affect the relationship between the two
countries, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Aminzada here today, Sharif expressed
his deep condolence over the death of the five Iranian air force
cadets, who were shot dead by unidentified gunmen in Rawalpindi,
the sister city of Islamabad, on September 17, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Sharif assured full cooperation of the government of Pakistan
in investigating the shooting case and said that the perpetrators
of this criminal act would not be able to evade justice.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also underscored their determination not to
allow such incidents to affect their countries' traditional
relationship, which they said was rooted deep in history, common
faith and shared cultural heritage.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani prime minister also said that he was looking
forward to meeting with Iranian leaders during the forthcoming
eighth summit of the Organization of the Islamic Conference to be
held in Tehran, Iran, in December 1997, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier the visiting Iranian deputy foreign minister also
called on Pakistani President Farooq Leghari and Foreign Minister
Gohar Ayub Khan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
