<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Rally Held in Somali to Mark Signing of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, October 17 (Xinhua) -- One of the largest peace
rallies took place today in south Mogadishu, capital of Somali
with supporters of the rival factions of Hussein Mohamed Aidid
and those of Osman Hassan Ali Atto participating.
</P>
<P>
The peace rally was held in support of the implementation of
the Sana peace agreement signed by Aidid and Osman Atto on May
12, 1997.
</P>
<P>
More than 5,000 people gathered today at the university hall
controlled by Osman Atto's faction to witness the great event in
which an eight-point agreement was signed by both sides.
</P>
<P>
Around the meeting hall, there were dozens of elders,
religious men, women and hundreds of militiamen from both sides
who embraced each other and cried for missing each other for so
long.
</P>
<P>
During the well participated ceremony, delegates from both
sides signed the eight-point agreement which ruled that both
sides should forgive each other and forget about the past.
</P>
<P>
The agreement prescribed the separation of the troops within
seven days, the formation of a joint committee within 48 hours to
oversee the implementation modalities of the agreed points and
that supporters of both sides living inside and outside the
country should help the fulfillment of this agreement.
</P>
<P>
It also called on the people to read Suratul Ikhlas (Koranic
sura usually read for the dead) for those who died during the
civil war between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
A considerable number of politicians, clan elites and other
dignitaries from all clans of Hawiye were invited to the
gathering. Between 5 and 40 dignitaries were invited from each
clan to witness the event which was held in a well decorated and
heavily fortified hall.
</P>
<P>
This important peace agreement was signed at a time when both
Hussein Aidid and Osman Atto are away from the country. However,
delegates representing them told reporters that things were going
on under the directives of their leaders and hoped that this
agreement would lead to a larger peace settlement for the
political crises of Somalia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
