<HEADLINE> DPRK Seizes Two South Korean Farmers in DMZ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Border soldiers of the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) seized two South Korean farmers
in the Demilitarized Zone (DMZ) today.
</P>
<P>
Military sources in the DPRK were quoted by South Korea's
Yonhap news agency as saying that the farmers were caught because
they had earlier crossed the military demarcation line, the center
line of the four-km-wide buffer zone, into the north.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean Defense Ministry reported earlier that the two
villagers were picking corn near the military demarcation line
just before noon when 12 DPRK troops crossed the demarcation line
and carried them into the north side.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said there was no exchange of fire between
soldiers of the two sides, and Pyongyang said, hours after the
seizure, it would return the two farmers.
</P>
<P>
The Military Armistice Commission held a meeting on the matter
at the truce village of Panmunjom, but this ended fruitlessly this
afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
