<HEADLINE> Russia's Situation Stable: Yeltsin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
said today the situation in Russia is under his "secure controls"
and he has options to resist the parliament's attacks.
</P>
<P>
Russia has a stable system of political power based on the
constitution, an Itar-Tass news agency report quoted the president
as saying in his weekly radio address.
</P>
<P>
With "secure controls" over the entire country, Yeltsin said,
he could choose between the resignation and the resolving of the
parliament if the State Duma, the lower house of parliament,
expresses its no-confidence over the government.
</P>
<P>
It was common to see conflicts between the parliament and the
government in developed countries, and the conflicts do not lead
to disasters, he said. "There is no disaster in Russia now either."
</P>
<P>
On the State Duma's request for the resignation of the
government over the 1998 budget dispute, Yeltsin called for
dialogues and compromises between the executive and legislative
branches.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the crisis would be resolved as soon as possible
with the cooperation of all parties.
</P>
<P>
The president also confirmed his initiative on holding a
roundtable of political parties and a meeting of the "Big Four" --
the president, the prime minister and the parliamentary speakers
-- on major controversies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
