<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Men Urged to Play Role in Breastfeeding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Australian federal Health
Minister Michael Wooldridge today called on Australian fathers to
promote breastfeeding by attaching importance to it and pitching
in with the housework for the good of their children.
</P>
<P>
The minister said lack of support by men was a key reason that
women gave up breastfeeding a new baby.
</P>
<P>
Men will be targeted in an Australian federal government-funded
campaign to boost breastfeeding, which Wooldridge said was a
factor in reduced ear and respiratory infections, allergies,
gastroenteritis, obesity and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
Wooldridge said the father's attitude was the single most
important factor in babies being breastfed until they were six
months old.
</P>
<P>
"One Australian study found that 97 percent of mothers
breastfed when the father supported breastfeeding - where they
didn't, the rate dropped by more than one quarter," he said in
Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
He announced that the Nursing Mothers' Association of Australia
(NMAA) had won a 255,000 US dollar tender for a two-year community
education campaign which will focus on helping men support their
partners.
</P>
<P>
The government wants to see 80 percent of babies breastfed
until six months of age.
</P>
<P>
This means doubling the current rate of breastfeeding by the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
At present 80 percent of women breastfeed at birth but this
drops to 60 percent by three months and 40 percent by six months.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wu Yanyan Sets Swimming World Record at National Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Wu Yanyan of Guangxi set a
world record in the women's 200 meters individual medley by
clocking two minutes 9.72 seconds at the Chinese Eighth National
Games here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The previous world mark of 2:11.65 was established by Lin Li of
Jiangsu province at the Barcelona Olympic Games on July 30, 1992.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning's Chen Yan, who broke the 400m individual medley on
Monday, was denied a chance today to win her fourth gold in the
National Games. The triple gold medalist finished second with
2:11.27, which was also a world-mark-breaking performance.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong's Sun Guiling wound up third with 2:13.94.
</P>
<P>
"It's a hard victory," said Wu. "Chen was chasing me very
closely. Of course, I was unlikely to break the world record
without her challenge."
</P>
<P>
Wu, 19, who won a silver in the 400m individual medley after
Chen, owned today's victory to an upper hand in the breaststroke.
</P>
<P>
"I know I will lose again if I cannot build a lead in the
breaststroke," Wu said. "Chen is much stronger in freestyle in the
last 50 meters."
</P>
<P>
Wu, who took a shine in China's Olympic trials but returned
home from Atlanta without any medal due to a poor health, has
focused on all her attention on the National Games since last
year.
</P>
<P>
Wu Jicai, Wu's coach for 12 years, played a very important role
in bring her out of the Olympic disappointment.
</P>
<P>
"I told her the defeat is a temperary thing and you should look
to the future," the 61-year-old Wu said.
</P>
<P>
"She trained too hard before the Atlanta Olympic Games and got
a fever just before the games," the coach said.
</P>
<P>
After one year of training, the Olympian's efforts eventually
were paid off, improving her best time of 2:12.87 by more than
three seconds.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 100m butterfly, local favorite Jiang Chengji
completed a gold double following his 100m freestyle triumph with
53.28 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Army's Zhu Yi retained his title in the men's 200m
breaststroke in 2:15.88 while the women's 4X100m medley relay also
went to the Army squad with 4:02.09. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Top Legislator Vows to Better Ties With Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Speaker of India's
lower house of parliament, Purno Sangma, has vowed to push ahead
his country's relations with Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
Sangma, here for a five-day visit ending today, reiterated the
need for both countries to speed up the implementation of
bilateral agreements on economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
During his stay, the top Indian legislator met Mongolian
President Nachagyn Bagabandy and Radnasumberlyn Gonchigdorzh,
chairman of the Great Hural, or the Mongolian parliament.
</P>
<P>
India attaches great importance to its relations with Mongolia,
and his visit was aimed at furthering the friendly cooperation
between the two countries, he noted.
</P>
<P>
In response, Mongolian leaders expressed satisfaction over
agricultural and live stock farming cooperation projects already
undertaking by the two sides.
</P>
<P>
There could be great potentials for extending cooperation among
the small and-medium-sized businesses of Mongolia and India, they
were quoted as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
