<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Jet Bomb Claims 8 in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Eight civilians died in the
east of the capital Thursday evening after a bomb dropped by a
Nigerian jet exploded at Kissy, doctors at the main hospital
said.
</P>
<P>
About 20 others were seriously injured. They were in a market
place when the bomb fell and the corpses were badly dismembered,
some without limbs or heads.
</P>
<P>
Two bombs were also dropped at Wilberforce and Lecester peak
by another jet. This is the first time two jets from west African
peace-keeping forces known as ECOMOG took part in the military
operation in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The bomb at Lecester peak damaged one of two solar panels of
the state-owned radio and TV station but no one was injured.
</P>
<P>
The blast instantly disrupted all radio and TV transmissions.
"We are lucky there is very little damage to the vital
equipment," said Gipu Felix George, director-general of
broadcasting, who visited the site an hour after the bombing.
</P>
<P>
The radio and TV station have been closed down for a couple of
days, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, military government leader Major Johnny Paul Koroma
urged demonstrating youths "not to destroy properties belonging
to their opponents but to allow the government to take its own
measures."
</P>
<P>
Koroma's appeal came after demonstrating youths set fire to at
least four houses belonging to supporters of ousted civilian
leader Tejan Kabbah in Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Furniture was taken out of the house of a former foreign
minister Desmong Luke and burnt in the street in the central part
of the capital.
</P>
<P>
"We decided not to burn the house as it is adjacent to a
petrol station," one youth explained to Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
In another development, diplomatic sources said Monday's
meeting in neighboring Guinea between the ECOWAS committee of
five and the Sierra Leone junta is "unlikely" to be held.
</P>
<P>
"Our information is that it will likely be either on Wednesday
or Thursday," one source said.
</P>
<P>
There are speculations on whether rebel leader Foday Sankoh,
now under house arrest in Nigeria, will be freed to take part in
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh is the deputy head of state in the military junta.
</P>
</TEXT>
