<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
form the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- The Cyprus economy is expected to grow by about 4
percent next year, up from an estimated 2.5 percent this year,
according to a report by the Planning Bureau and the Ministry of
Finance today.
</P>
<P>
The joint report, presented to the House of Representatives,
says the economic prospects for 1998 are encouraging, mainly
because of a more favorable climate both abroad and at home.
</P>
<P>
The report says the agricultural sector is expected to pick
up, especially if weather conditions improve, while services,
which contribute to some 71 percent of the gross domestic product
(GDP), will continue to play a major role in economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment is expected to fall to 3 percent from the
present 3.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The world's top oil producer and exporter Saudi
Arabia announced that it discovered two new gas fields with
reserves of 7.5 trillion cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi Press Agency quoted Saudi Oil Minister Ali-Nueimi as
saying that the discovery would raise Saudi gas reserves to a total
of 204 trillion cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
The two new gas fields were named as Al-Qateef and Al-Teenat by
the Saudi National Oil Company "Aramco," the agency said.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- The slowdown in the Cypriot stock market's retreat
last week led to a small advance this week, according to a report
issued by the Cyprus Investment and Securities Corporation Limited
(CISCO).
</P>
<P>
The CISCO All-Share Index closed Thursday at 386.4 points,
with a weekly improvement of 3.6 points.
</P>
<P>
Buying of selected stocks by institutional investors this week
seems to have provided the necessary stimulation in the market,
Encouraging prospects on how the economy will fare in the current
year and in 1998 also have positively contributed to the gradual
restoration of negative investor psychology.
</P>
<P>
The total weekly volume of transactions reached 2.6 million
Cyprus pounds (about 5.2 million U.S. dollars) this week,
compared to 2.5 million pounds (5 million dollars) last
week.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Kuwaiti government sold 30 million shares in
the Commercial Bank of Kuwait (CBK) worth 10 million Kuwaiti
dinars (33 million U.S. dollars) to a commercial bank.
</P>
<P>
General Manager of Kuwait Stock Exchange Hisham Al-Otaibi said
the shares were acquired in an open auction by the commercial
National Bank of Kuwait which put up the highest price among six
bidders.
</P>
<P>
The government held 12 percent of overall CBK shares totalling
1.06 billion before today's auction.
</P>
<P>
The second phase of floating the government's shares in the CBK
would start soon and would involve 70 million shares.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwait's Ministry of Water and Electricity said
more new water distillation units will be established by the turn
of the century to meet the increasing water consumption demands.
</P>
<P>
An annual statistical report by the ministry said a tender
would be placed in mid-1998 for the establishment of the first
phase of water distillation units in Al-Sabiyah station located in
eastern Kuwait which will be operation in 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
