<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 12:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Denies Intention to Attend Doha Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Egypt today denied that it wants
to take part in the fourth Middle East and North Africa (MENA)
Economic Summit to be held in Doha, the Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a Foreign Ministry spokesman as saying Egypt
maintains its firm stance that its participation in Doha
conference hinges on a shift in the Israeli policy towards the
Mideast peace march.
</P>
<P>
"What have been mentioned by one of the U.S. official spokesmen
on Egypt's intention to attend the conference are groundless,"
said the spokesman, who is customarily not identified.
</P>
<P>
A final decision on whether Egypt will attend will be announced
in due time prior to the convocation of the conference, he said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman James Robin claimed on
Wednesday that the U.S. received pledges from a number of Arab
countries, including Egypt, to take part in the conference slated
for November.
</P>
<P>
Most Arab countries have either flatly rejected or threatened
to boycott the conference which will include Israel given the
Mideast peace process is going through a problematic phase.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has been assiduously trying to talk the Arab countries
into attending the conference, even at lower levels, for its
symbolic value of an Arab-Israeli rapport.
</P>
<P>
As a direct spinoff of the peace process that started in 1991,
the annual MENA conference had been held in Casablanca, Amman and
Cairo since 1994. But peace prospects have generally deteriorated
since then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
