<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Emergency Relief Efforts Taken in Quake-Stricken Chile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Chile's Interior Minister
Carlos Figueroa today announced a series of emergency relief
measures to help people in the country's earthquake-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
The measures, Figueroa said, included declaring the Fourth
Region, which was worst hit in the quake on Tuesday, as a disaster
area to make residents there eligible for more relief funding.
</P>
<P>
In addition, they also called for the establishment of two
committees to mobilize the resources of six government ministries
in undertaking relief and reconstruction efforts respectively.
</P>
<P>
The decisions were made at a meeting of cabinet ministers
presided over by President Eduardo Frei, and ministries were asked
to earmark special funding for supporting the relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
The Fourth Region of Coquimbo, with the regional capital at La
Serena, has been declared national disaster area for several times
in recent years due to either drought or flooding.
</P>
<P>
The latest devastation it sustained was the earthquake
measuring 6.8 on the Richter scale, which killed eight people and
injured nearly 100 others in central and northern Chile.
</P>
<P>
While about 3,000 residential houses were destroyed and 5,000
more damaged, some 15,000 people were left homeless.
</P>
<P>
Figueroa said his ministry is sending emergency relief goods,
as well as badly needed financial assistance, into the cities and
towns and more than 700 rural villages in the quake-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted, the early arrival of the help was hampered
by the poor conditions of the road leading to these areas, caused
earlier by flooding and lately by the quake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, African Trade Union Symposium In Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 17 (Xinhua) -- A symposium on Chinese and
African trade union work in the increasingly globalized economy,
sponsored by the All-China Federation of Trade Unions (CFTU) and
the Organization of African Trade Union Unity (OATUU), opened
here today.
</P>
<P>
CFTU and OATUU representatives, and trade union representatives
from Cote d'Ivoire, Algeria, Niger, Togo, Rwanda, Benin, Cameroon,
Madagascar, and other countries were present at today's ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Li Qisheng, vice-president of CFTU, addressed the gathering,
saying that globalization and regionalization of the world's
economies has, to a certain extent, provided an opportunity for
promoting national economies and creating more employment, but has
also seriously challenged all countries, especially developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries, especially the African countries, have
suffered a lot because of an irrational international economic
order, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Many countries' trade unions are paying close attention to the
influence of economic globalization on labor, he said, and in
order to promote the national economies and safeguard the rights
and interests of workers, trade unions have done a great deal of
work.
</P>
<P>
So, the symposium is significant as a place where participants
can discuss economic globalization's influence on national
economic development, employee-employer relations in
foreign-funded enterprises, trade union work, increasing
solidarity and co-operation between trade unions of developing
countries, and safeguarding workers' rights.
</P>
<P>
OATUU representative Mujyambere Augustin said that trade unions
should intensify their work, reconsider their own structure, and
strengthen solidarity to resist the harmful influences of economic
globalization.
</P>
<P>
He said he is satisfied with the good relations between OATUU
and CFTU and that the symposium will fuel co-operative relations
between CFTU and African trade unions.
</P>
<P>
Participants will also visit the Tianjin Economic and
Technological Development Zone and large state-run enterprises and
foreign-funded enterprises.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Capital Building Finance Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 17 (Xinhua) -- A finance street in Beijing
that the Municipal Government began planning in 1993 in the
western part of the city, is now taking shape.
</P>
<P>
Major Chinese banking institutions, including the headquarters
of the Peoples Bank of China, the People's Insurance Corporation
of China and the Bank of China, are lining up to get into the
88-ha. area with more than two million sq.m. of floor space. The
infrastructure cost 200 million US dollars to build.
</P>
<P>
The city wants to make it a multi-purpose administrative and
information center for banking and the securities and insurance
businesses.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this year, there will be 14 of China's leading
financial institutions there like the Construction Bank of China
(CBC) and the Industrial and Commercial Bank of China, the China
Securities Regulatory Commission, the Ping An Insurance Co.,
Merchant Bank, Communications Bank, CITIC Industrial Bank of
China, and the China Investment Bank.
</P>
<P>
Major international financial institutions are expected to have
offices there. Eleven foreign banks have branches in Beijing, and
200 overseas financial institutions have offices.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's status as the nation's capital and political and
cultural center have attracted foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, the street will become a modernized community
focusing on financial business, according to the city's plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
