<HEADLINE> Israel Fears Sexual Complaint Harm Ties With Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Israel is concerned that the
sexual assault complaint against Egyptian Ambassador Mohammed
Bassiouny could adversely affect its relations with Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Official sources in Jerusalem were quoted by Israel Radio as
saying today that they fear the embarrassment the incident caused
Bassiouny will be played up in Cairo's generally hostile
newspapers, and in turn will further aggravate the Egyptian
public's ill will toward Israel.
</P>
<P>
They also feared that the publicity over the incident will harm
efforts to win the release of Azzam Azzam, an Israeli citizen
imprisoned in Cairo for espionage.
</P>
<P>
Bassiouny, the Egyptian ambassador serving the post ever since
the two countries forged diplomatic relations in 1979, has been
investigated by Israeli police over the past two months for
alleged indecent advances to an Israeli belly dancer after
inviting her to a friend's apartment.
</P>
<P>
The belly dancer complained to the police, claiming that
Bassiouny had promised to use his connections to advance her
career. The woman's lover reportedly urged her to file the
complaint in a bid to blackmail the ambassador.
</P>
<P>
The information about the investigation had been barred from
the news media and was exposed only after the complaint was
dismissed by State Attorney Edna Arbel on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Ministry Director-General Eitan Bentsur offered
an apology to Bassiouny Thursday, saying Israel condemned the
harassment to him by the media and expressing the intention to
continue cooperation with him.
</P>
<P>
Bentsur also praised Bassiouny for his contribution to the
Middle East peace process and the Egyptian-Israeli relations.
</P>
<P>
Bassiouny said he was pleased that the case had been closed and
satisfied with the stand taken by the Israeli government during
the investigation. The incident would not affect relationship
between two countries, the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
Local news agency, Itim, said that Bassiouny affair was known
at the highest level including the president, prime minister and
foreign minister, "each of whom followed the progress of the
police inquiry very closely." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
