<HEADLINE> Cyprus Forecasts 4 Percent GDP Growth in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus economy is expected
to grow by about 4 percent next year, up from an estimated 2.5
percent this year, according to a report by the Planning Bureau
and the Ministry of Finance today.
</P>
<P>
The joint report, presented to the House of Representatives,
says the economic prospects for 1998 are encouraging, mainly
because of a more favorable climate both abroad and at home.
</P>
<P>
The report says the agricultural sector is expected to pick
up, especially if weather conditions improve, while services,
which contribute to some 71 percent of the gross domestic product
(GDP), will continue to play a major role in economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment is expected to fall to 3 percent from the
present 3.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
It forecasts a 2.5 percent growth in GDP in real terms for this
year. By the end of this year, it says, tourism will increase by
5 percent with the number of visitors exceeding the 2 million
figure, compared to 1.95 million in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
