<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Azerbaijian Calls for Peace-Keepers in Nagorno-Karabakh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Azerbaijian today made a fresh
call for the dispatch of international peace-keeping forces to the
breakaway Nagorno-Karabakh region, said an Interfax news agency
report.
</P>
<P>
The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE)
must send troops to help implement the principles for bringing
peace to the region, President Geidar Aliyev was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Aliyev's made the remarks at a graduation ceremony of the air
force's pilot training school while commenting on the OSCE's
proposal for resolving the issue that also involves Armenia.
</P>
<P>
Armenia, a neighbor of Azerbaijian, has a military presence in
Nagorno-Karabakh to back the region's request for independence.
</P>
<P>
The OSCE formulated a series of principles at its December 1996
summit in Lisbon, Portugal, calling for granting Nagorno-Karabakh
a high degree of autonomy while keeping it within Azerbaijian.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the Minsk group of the OSCE, consisting of
representatives from Russia, France and other European nations,
proposed accomplishing the peace process in two steps.
</P>
<P>
As the first step, some Armenian forces would leave the region
and refugees would return; and in the second step, all Armenian
troops would be out and the region would gain an autonomous status.
</P>
<P>
Azerbaijian wants to have a peaceful end to the armed conflict
in Nagorno-Karabakh, Aliyev said today, adding that his government
has agreed in principle on the OSCE group's proposal.
</P>
<P>
On Azerbaijian's military power, the president said his country
now has its own regular armed forces and their current task for
the time being is to enhance combat capabilities.
</P>
<P>
The military has a mandate to defend the country's national
sovereignty and territorial integrity, he said.
</P>
<P>
In a related development today, Levon Zubadryan, press
secretary to Armanian President Levon Ter-Petrocyan, reportedly
said local authorities of Nagorno-Karabakh had already rejected
the Minsk group's initiative.
</P>
<P>
Armenia will join in future talks for a peace plan acceptable
for all parties involved in the conflict, Zubadryan said. And it
will endorse any document signed by Nagorno-Karabakh.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President Ter-Petrocyan told a news conference in
Erivan that talks on the Nagorno-Karabakh issue could be fruitful
only if representatives from the region are allowed to take part.
</P>
<P>
However, the Azerbaijiani government has a consistent policy of
denying the region's independence request and has been refusing to
have any contact with its representatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
