<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Coral Reefs in Shocking Condition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's coral reefs are
among the least healthy in the world, ravaged by over-fishing,
dynamiting and poison fishing, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Shocking results of the first global survey of coral reefs,
which looked at 300 sites in 30 countries and regions this summer,
were revealed here Thursday by the Reef Check '97 project.
</P>
<P>
Global coordinator of the project Gregor Hodgson said the
results showed there has been "serious damage" to worldwide coral
reefs, which are in much worse shape than previously thought.
</P>
<P>
Commercial fish and shellfish are absent from most sites, he
said.
</P>
<P>
In Hong Kong, over-exploitation led to the near-extinction of
creatures such as the spiny lobster, which was abundant less than
20 years ago, said Hodgson, who is also a marine biologist with
Hong Kong University of Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
Of 11 species of fish or shellfish the researchers used as
"indicator species," only two, Trochus shells and butterfly fish,
were found in Hong Kong reefs.
</P>
<P>
Coral reefs, called "rain forests of the ocean," are one of the
world's most valuable natural resources, Hodgson said. He
advocated protected marine areas, regulation of fishing practices
and development of artificial reefs to provide breeding grounds
for reef species.
</P>
<P>
More than 800 scientists and divers participated in the
survey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Take Measures Against Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese government is
poised to step up efforts to intensify its drive against smuggling
and commercial fraud, the Vietnamese press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Phan Van Khai has ordered the General Department
of Customs and Ministries of Interior, Trade and Finance to take
drastic measures to stop smuggling over the sea and on land.
</P>
<P>
Phan also required government institutions, national or local,
to inspect the business activities, financial and accounting
records of all import-export companies under their supervision.
</P>
<P>
He ordered severe and due punishment for all smuggling and
cheating cases, and immediate trials for a number of typical
smuggling cases in order to warn against other potential offenders.
</P>
<P>
The head of government stressed that all foreign imports
without legal clearance document will be considered as smuggled
goods and be confiscated, and their owners will be punished.
</P>
</TEXT>
