<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela's Libya Trip Won't Violate UN Sanctions: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 17 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela's trip to Tripoli, Libya by land next week would
not be violating United Nations sanctions against Libya, Foreign
Ministry spokesman Peter Swanepoel said today.
</P>
<P>
Swanepoel's remarks were clearly in response to concerns of
the United States over the visit.
</P>
<P>
The United States Thursday expressed disapproval of Mandela's
state visit to Libya.
</P>
<P>
"We would reiterate the fact that, according to UN Security
Council Resolutions 748 and 883, flights into Tripoli are a
violation of sanctions. So I think that would be a very specific
concern," State Department spokesman James Foley said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We also believe that diplomatic contacts ought to be
maintained at a low level, and we would be disappointed with the
visit of any head of state," he added.
</P>
<P>
The United States regards Libya as a sponsor of international
terrorism and seeks to isolate it politically and economically.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations banned flights to and from Libya because of
Tripoli's refusal to extradite two suspects for the 1988 downing
of a Pan Am airliner over Rockerbie, Scotland. The downing of the
plane by bombs killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
Swanepoel said Mandela's state visit to Libya would not affect
South Africa's relations with the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Through the bi-national commission we keep one another
informed of our different positions," he said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministry spokesman added that the South African
government was well aware of the position of the United States,
but that South Africa also had bilateral relations with Libya,
which is a fellow member of the Organization of African Unity
(OAU).
</P>
<P>
On the UN sanctions on flights into Libya, Swanepoel said
Mandela would be travelling by road from southern Tunisia to
Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
"The president won't be breaking any sanctions, he's not
flying in and out."
</P>
<P>
South Africa has insisted on developing relations with Libya,
Iran and Cuba, defying pressure and warning from the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, who plans to visit Egypt and Libya before attending
the Commonwealth heads of state meeting in Edinburg, Scotland on
October 24-27, is expected to broker some sort of resolution on
Rockerbie bombing.
</P>
<P>
Libya, backed by the OAU and the Non-Aligned Movement, has
suggested a compromise, calling for the trial to be held in a
neutral country, by Scottish judges under Scottish law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
