<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Govt Spending Beyond Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The South African
government is overspending financial budget, which, some
economists said, is likely to put Finance Minister Trevor
Manuel's ambitious budget targets in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
According to exchequer figures released on Thursday night, the
government spending for the first six months of the fiscal year
was up 11.5 percent over that of the same period last year,
compared with a budgeted rise in spending of only 6.1 percent for
1997/98.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Department tried to slash government spending in
real terms this fiscal year beginning April to reduce the deficit
and free up saving for the private sector.
</P>
<P>
A reduction in the deficit to four percent of Gross Domestic
Product is a crucial first step toward the growth targets in
growth, employment and redistribution (Gear) strategy worked out
by the South African government.
</P>
<P>
Local press quoted economists as saying that they were
increasingly worried that the fiscal targets would not be met,
which would be bad omen for Gear. Spending overruns are also
likely to harm fragile investor confidence, they said.
</P>
<P>
Economist Dawie Roodt said, to meet the targets, non-interest
expenditure would have to fall slightly in nominal terms for the
remainder of the fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
"It is difficult to see how government will be able to achieve
that. Manuel is facing a big problem," Roodt said.
</P>
<P>
However, finance officials remained optimistic that the
targets could be met, saying the figure in the monthly exchequer
statement represented requests from departments and provinces for
funds to spend, rather than actual spending.
</P>
<P>
The final spending figures could be less, the officials said,
adding that they were working hard with provincial governments to
resolve the problems.
</P>
<P>
Finance Director-General Maria Ramos said last week she was
"still optimistic" about the deficit target.
</P>
<P>
"It is true expenditure is higher in the first half than we
wanted it to be, but we are likely to see a significant slowdown
in the second half. We are working closely with the provinces to
sort things out," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
