<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Development Assistance to Poor Countries Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Development assistance to
developing countries fell by 3.8 billion U.S. Dollars in 1996, a
decline of 4.2 percent from 1995, a leading British aid agency
named Action Aid said in a report.
</P>
<P>
The report, entitled "The Reality of Aid 1997/98", noted that
the biggest cut came from Japan which reduced its aid to
developing countries by 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that in 1995, 17 out of 21 Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) donors cut their aid
to sub-Saharan Africa while a quarter of the total OECD aid
reached the 48 least developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Insufficient aid is being channelled to those countries which
need it most while the wealthier states in central and eastern
Europe have enjoyed a 10 percent increase in aid, added the
report, which came out on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report stressed that the world's rich countries were not
committed to eradicating global poverty, particularly in the most
disadvantaged countries in the South, mostly in Africa.
</P>
<P>
There is little indication that the OECD countries would
reverse the trend, which is blamed on the end of the Cold War,
the report noted.
</P>
<P>
Development assistance to Kenya dropped by 21 percent between
1991 and 1995 while external aid to the country accounts for 10
percent of Kenya's gross national product. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
