<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Finance Ministry Lists New Budget Focus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Preparations for Nigeria's 1998
budget have begun in earnest with the Finance Ministry listing 19
priority projects and programs to be accomplished within the
scope of the budget.
</P>
<P>
According to a ministry circular to various related ministries
and departments, the 19 priority projects and programs are to be
assessed under three categories.
</P>
<P>
These are ongoing projects which have gone beyond 70 percent
completion and can be competed before the end of the the next
fiscal year, and rehabilitation projects or those that will
enhance the utilization or performance of existing projects and
programs, as well as ongoing projects which are critical to the
statutory responsibilities of ministries and agencies.
</P>
<P>
The budget, in addition to other development plans, is aimed
at improving the performance of some key macro-economic
aggregates, which hitherto has showed sluggish response to the
various economic policies, the Punch newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the goal, 10 main objectives and policy thrusts
have been sent out which the capital projects are expected to
help achieve, the circular said.
</P>
<P>
The objectives include the expansion of the revenue base of
government, continuation of government's policy of deregulation,
as well as employment generation through poverty alleviation
programs.
</P>
<P>
The 19 projects and programs, according to the circular, cover
food production, iron and steel production, railways, machine
tools, solid minerals, security agencies, power plants, education
and health care.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of all ministries, agencies and
extra-ministerial departments started discussions on proposals to
the budget on September 29. 
</P>
</TEXT>
