<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 09:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Union Strike Blacks Out Parts of Beirut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Power cuts and rationing
plunged parts of the capital and other areas in Lebanon into
darkness last night as the strike of Electricite du Liban (EDL)'s
employees ran into its third day.
</P>
<P>
According to local newspaper the Daily Star, the strike, which
started on Tuesday to protest the company's failure to meet the
employees' demands for higher pay, benefits and better conditions,
was echoed by nearly 5,000 employees across the country.
</P>
<P>
The employees refused to repair damages to the electricity
network and collect bill.
</P>
<P>
According to EDL sources, the most affected region until
Thursday was Beirut's southern suburbs, where 12 power units
supplying the area broke down.
</P>
<P>
Damage to the network was also reported in other areas like
Sidon, the biggest city in south Lebanon. The paper quoted a
worker, who requested anonymity, as saying that "At least 10
incidents of damage are reported on a normal day."
</P>
<P>
"After four days of being on strike the damages have
definitely piled up," he said, "We even got threats of violence
from people in the suburbs" against the workers' decision not to
repair damages.
</P>
<P>
Ali Ayoub, head of the company's union, acknowledged that he
would agree to suspend the strike, which has only brought
negative and discouraging results, in the light of four of their
demands having been met by the company.
</P>
<P>
A meeting between the representatives of employees and the
company administration is underway, and there are signs that the
strike would end today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
