<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-U.S. Joint Venture to Produce Silicon Chips </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUOYANG, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The first Sino-American silicon
chips joint venture began operation today in Luoyang, an ancient
city in central China's Henan province.
</P>
<P>
The MCL Electronic Material Ltd. Company is a joint venture
between America's MEMC Electronic Material Company and China Sijia
Semiconductor Materials Company.
</P>
<P>
MEMC, a specialist in silicon chip manufacturing, offers
advanced technology with a 20 percent market share, while Sijia is
China's largest semiconductor producer.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture is expected to sell 85 percent of its
products to the United States, Singapore, Malaysia, the Republic
of Korea, India, Taiwan and Hong Kong. The venture also is
expected to meet the needs of China's domestic electronics
industry.
</P>
<P>
MCL has spent more than 15 million U.S. dollars erecting 3,500
square meters of high-purity factory buildings and sanitary
workshops.
</P>
<P>
The company has introduced sophisticated production and
quality-control equipment for integrated circuit board products,
advanced technology and management expertise.
</P>
<P>
The company sent 10 engineers and managers to the United
States, Malaysia and Italy in the past year for training on the
production process for 100mm and 125mm silicon chips.
</P>
<P>
The company expects to produce 100,000 silicon chips every
month beginning in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
