<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Unveils Surplus Budget for 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia today announced a
surplus Budget for 1998 with measures which seeks to restore more
aggressively investor confidence in Malaysia in the aftermath of
the currency and stock market turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the Budget in Parliament here today, Malaysian
Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim said "Our economy is at a
crossroad. The direction of the economy is currently fraught with
uncertainties. The crisis in the financial markets is a test of
economic resilience and the effectiveness of policies."
</P>
<P>
Anwar, who is also Finance Minister, said the 1998 Budget
strategy is: strengthening economic fundamentals and stabilizing
financial markets; maintaining sustainable growth; continuing the
process of deregulation and liberalization of the economy; and
continuing the social agenda for further overall development.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 Budget has a total expenditure package of 64.124
billion ringgit (about 20.038 billion U.S. dollars) for 1998
against the Federal government revenue estimated to be at 68.058
billion ringgit (about 21.268 billion U.S. dollars), showing a
surplus of 3.934 billion ringgit (about 1.23 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Taking into account the loan repayments and transfers, the
overall surplus will be at 8.951 billion ringgit (about 2.797
billion U.S. dollars), or 3.2 percent of Gross National Product
(GNP), Anwar said.
</P>
<P>
The total allocation for 1998 represents an increase of 1.9
percent over the 1997 total allocation of about 60 billion
ringgit.
</P>
<P>
Of the total for the coming year, 45.633 billion ringgit (about
14.26 billion U.S. dollars) are allocated for operating
expenditure, up 1.7 percent as compared to the 1997 allocation,
and 18.491 billion ringgit (about 5.778 billion U.S. dollars) for
development.
</P>
<P>
Out of the development allocation, a sum of 8.828 billion
ringgit or 47.7 percent is for the economic sector, 5.890 billion
ringgit or 31.9 percent for the social sector, 2.433 billion
ringgit or 13.2 percent for the security sector and 840 million
ringgit or 4.5 percent for the General Services Sector, and the
balance of 500 million ringgit or 2.7 percent for the contingency
reserve.
</P>
<P>
Anwar announced steps to reduce the current account deficit,
increase export competitiveness, cut imports, increase import
duties for luxury items including cars, and further deregulate and
liberalize the economy.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said Malaysia is expected to register a moderate growth
of 7.0 percent in 1998, reflecting slower expansion of world
trade, slower rate of growth in demand and income as well as a
deceleration in agriculture output.
</P>
<P>
He said "We are confident that we can attain the forecast
growth if productivity and competitiveness can be improved."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
