<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nanjing Museum Receives German Rabe's Belongings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, October 17 (Xinhua) -- An album and bronze cigar case
which belonged to John Rabe have been added to the long list of
relics housed in a Nanjing museum commemorating people massacred
during the Rape of Nanjing in 1937.
</P>
<P>
Ursula Reinhardt, Rabe's granddaughter, donated the items
during a recent visit to the city.
</P>
<P>
Rabe, who worked for the Shanghai office of German-based
Siemens from 1931-1938, helped protect more than 200,000 refugees
in Nanjing, east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
Rabe later returned to Germany and was arrested for disclosing
atrocities committed by invading Japanese forces.
</P>
<P>
A group of Nanjing residents sent the poverty-stricken Rabe a
gift of 2,000 US dollars and food in 1948.
</P>
<P>
The commemorative album, which recorded the generous gift by
appreciative and sympathetic Nanjingers, remained in the hands of
Rabe's family until the recent donation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
