<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombo Bombing Won't Affect Sri Lanka's Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The massive explosion in
downtown of Sri Lanka's capital Colombo on Wednesday will not
affect the country's tourism industry, the Association of Group
Tourist Agents (AGTA) said today.
</P>
<P>
The swift handling of the aftermath by the government has
restored the confidence of the tourism industry, the AGTA said.
</P>
<P>
Though the attack was a set-back to the industry, AGTA
officials said they were confident the impact would be minimal.
</P>
<P>
One foreign tourist was among the 16 dead and 32 foreigners
were among the 108 injured in the bombing attack which seriously
damaged two five-star hotels, the Hilton and Galadari.
</P>
<P>
Police said the bombing attack was carried out by members of
the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, which has been fighting a
14-year-long ethnic war for a separate state of their own in the
north and east of the country.
</P>
<P>
Some tourism analysts expect tourist arrivals to drop in the
next few months but the AGTA said they had no intention of
canceling reservations made for the coming months.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's tourism industry, which was badly affected in 1996
because of the bombing of the Central Bank and a passenger train
at Dehiwela near Colombo, has recovered considerably this year due
to improved security conditions.
</P>
<P>
Up to July this year, tourist arrivals rose by 21 percent to
237,100 compared to 194,800 during the corresponding period the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
At a presidential news conference this morning, Tourism and
Aviation Minister Dharmasiri Senanayake said a total of 494
tourists arrived at Colombo on Thursday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
