<HEADLINE> PNA Weighs Reopening Hamas Institutions: Radio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) is considering reopening the Hamas institutions
which were closed in the recent crackdown on terror, Israel Radio
reported today.
</P>
<P>
PNA Cabinet Secretary Abdul Rahman has informed leaders of the
Islamic Resistance Movement in Gaza that PNA President Yasser
Arafat would appoint a committee to review whether the
institutions could resume activities, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The PNA move came after the return to Gaza of Hamas founder and
spiritual leader Sheikh Ahmed Yassin early the month, which has
brought considerable pressure on Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Yassin was freed by Israel in a deal with Jordan in exchange
for the release of two secret Mossad agents captured by Jordanian
police in a failed assassination attempt on a Hamas political
leader in Amman on September 25.
</P>
<P>
This gave a boost to the Islamic militant group, which has
claimed responsibility for a series of bombing attacks against
Israel with the goal to liberate all Palestine land. Twenty-five
people including five bombers were killed and 300 others wounded
in the latest two attacks in two central Jerusalem markets.
</P>
<P>
Although it gained fame through terror attacks carried out by
its secret military wing Izzadin Kassim, Hamas is in fact
primarily a political organization deeply-rooted in the
Palestinian society.
</P>
<P>
It has been running a wide network of charity institutions,
including schools, day-care centers and clinics, to serve the need
of the poor and neglected. Israel insists that they are the
infrastructure that supports the Hamas terrorism and demands the
PNA dismantle them.
</P>
<P>
Under the pressure from both Israel and the United States,
Arafat promised tougher security measures by arresting a large
number of Hamas activists and shutting down several of their
institutions. But Yassin's release has both undermined the Israeli
demand for security and weakened PNA's ability to continue the
crackdown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
