<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan President Urges Tamils to Support Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga today called upon all Tamils and all citizens to give
their fullest support to her government's efforts to solve the
problems of the Tamil people and finish the never-ending-cycle of
terrible violence.
</P>
<P>
At a presidential news conference, the president said: "I
believe the Tamil people of Sri Lanka have no other alternative,
they have to support this government's policy which is the only
way out."
</P>
<P>
She expressed her determination to end the war successfully and
bring in the political solutions her government has proposed.
</P>
<P>
She said every evidence pointed to the fact that the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam had conspired the bombing of downtown
Colombo Wednesday morning, which killed 11 people and injured 108
others. Five LTTE rebels were shot dead by the security forces in
a crossfire following the explosion.
</P>
<P>
She also appealed the main opposition party, the United
National Party (UNP), to take a stand on "the only political
solution that have been offered by any government."
</P>
<P>
"It is time for the UNP to stop its politics of silence, it is
time for them to speak and tell the country what their stand is on
the solution we have proposed to end the war and to bring peace
back again to this country," the president said.
</P>
<P>
She accused some of the private media which had been sending
untrue reports with regard to the Colombo bombing and described
them as "irresponsible."
</P>
<P>
She said, contrary to those reports "that are full of complete
lies," the security forces was in total control in less than a few
minutes of the explosion site and of the whole of Colombo city and
the government is in total control of the situation now.
</P>
<P>
The government hopes to finish reconstruction of all the
damaged buildings, several of them in a few weeks and the others
in a few months, she said.
</P>
<P>
She pledged to give support, financially and in every other
way, to the private institutions that were seriously damaged in
the explosion to undertake the reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
The terrorist attack "has not deterred us in any way in any of
the major programs that the government has undertaken in the past
few years and has been implementing," she noted.
</P>
<P>
"This act will set us back for a few months, but I wish to
state that in the same way we bounced back after the terrorist
attack (on the Central Bank) nearly two years ago, we are bouncing
back, we shall recover," she added.
</P>
<P>
Also on the news conference, Tourism Minister Dharmasiri
Senanayake said the country's tourism industry, a cornerstone the
Sri Lanka's economy, was not affected by the bombing.
</P>
<P>
He said till now there has been no cancellation of tourist
charters and a total of 494 tourists arrived at Colombo on
Thursday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
