<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Provinces Join Forces to Find Jobs for Rural Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Provinces in China are
beginning to cooperate in dealing with the once aimless exodus of
rural laborers without jobs.
</P>
<P>
South China's Guangdong Province, which became the country's
largest employer with its booming economic growth, has initiated
cooperative relations with other provinces to deal with migrant
workers returning from Spring Festival.
</P>
<P>
Under the guidance of the Ministry of Labor, this kind of
inter-regional cooperation has been expanded to more provinces.
Now, a South China Labor Market Information Network has been put
into use, linking eight provinces in the area, centered around
Guangdong.
</P>
<P>
The network's Guangdong Center has also connected with the
networks of the Ministry of Labor, north China, and east China to
provide more data for accommodating a surplus rural labor force.
</P>
<P>
Inter-provincial cooperation now focuses on management of
employment identity cards, which serve as a certificate for
migrant workers to seek jobs.
</P>
<P>
A growing number of provinces, municipalities and autonomous
regions have seen the benefits and are working in cooperation to
find work for the jobless, said Sun Qingqi, deputy-director of the
Guangdong Provincial Labor Department.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
