<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Phase out Chemical Pesticides in Flower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan flower industry has
identified a number of alternative pesticides for the production
of cut flowers and gradually phased out the use of methyl
bromide, the paper "Daily Nation" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the Naivasha-based Sulmac Flower Farm,
the biggest one in the country, had reportedly reduced its
consumption of methyl bromide by 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
Jack Juma of the company told an on-going workshop on Thursday
that Sulmac was aimed at completely stopping the use of methyl
bromide by June 1998.
</P>
<P>
Initially, he said, the company, which grows roses,
chrysanthemums and carnations for export, is reducing the area
under the chemical from 140 hectares to 25 hectares.
</P>
<P>
Sulmac used to be the biggest consumer of methyl bromide in
this east African country, importing 80 tons each year for soil
disinfestation.
</P>
<P>
Methyl bromide, a popular soil fumigant in the floriculture
industry, is one of the ozone-depleting substances targeted for
phasing out internationally.
</P>
<P>
According to the Montreal Protocol agreements, while developed
countries are expected to freeze the production and use of methyl
bromide by 2002, developing countries should have done the same
by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries should completely phase out methyl
bromide by 2015 while developed countries should have
accomplished the same by 2005.
</P>
<P>
A representative of Colombia, the world's number two exporter
of cut flowers, told the workshop that his country had completely
phased out the use of methyl bromide in the production of
flowers.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is ranked third biggest cut flower exporter in the world
while the Netherlands is first. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0128 </DOCNO>
