<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 12,000 Kids Abducted in N. Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- About 12,000 children have
been abducted from northern Uganda by the rebels of the Lord's
Resistance Army (LRA) over the last five years, reported "the
Monitor" daily today.
</P>
<P>
Kathleen Cravero, representative of the United Nations
Children Fund to Uganda, was quoted as saying that 50 percent of
these are feared dead while 25 percent have returned.
</P>
<P>
According to Cravero, about 70 percent of the abducted are
between ages of 12 and 15 and 50 percent are boys, 40 percent
girls and 10 percent adults.
</P>
<P>
Among the abducted girls, she said, only 10 percent of the
them have returned.
</P>
<P>
Cravero reviewed that this was possible because the girls are
made wives of the rebel commanders and are always near the camps,
giving them less chances of escaping.
</P>
<P>
Cravero disclosed that 80 percent of the abduction occur in
Gulu and Kitgum districts where the LRA rebels -- Christian
fundamentalists -- have been distablizing for the last 10 years,
though some have taken place in Moyo, Lira and Apac districts as
well as in northern Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Cravero noted that more and more children are being
abducted in western districts of Kasese and Bundibugyo by the
rebels of Allied Democratic Forces who seems to copy LRA.
</P>
<P>
According to Cravero, 90 percent of abduction occur at home,
school and community places like water sources.
</P>
<P>
Cravero condemned LRA rebels for involving children in the
war.
</P>
<P>
"The problem has been more pronounced in the last three years
because voluntary recruitment into LRA seems to have dwindled
almost to nil," she said, adding that children's rights have been
violated, including witnessing murder of fellow children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
