<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Women Have Bigger Say in Family Life (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 17 (Xinhua) -- China traditionally has been
considered a country where the husband dominates and the wife has
less power in decision-making on major family issues.
</P>
<P>
However, drastic changes have occurred according to a recent
survey which found that more than 93 percent of Chinese urban
women have the responsibility of managing the family's income.
</P>
<P>
The survey by the Population Research Institute of the Chinese
Academy of Social Sciences (CASS) was conducted in Shanghai City,
Guangdong, Shandong, Jilin and Shaanxi provinces, and the Ningxia
Hui Autonomous Region. Results were announced at the ongoing
General Population Conference.
</P>
<P>
The survey reveals that the key to women's economic status in
family life is their income. The majority of Chinese women now
have an independent income and share common power with their
husbands in managing the family's economic activities, the survey
shows.
</P>
<P>
The rising economic status of women also has brought enormous
change to their thinking about child-bearing, divorce and other
issues, the survey reveals.
</P>
<P>
Chinese wives now play a bigger role in decisions on
child-bearing, according to the survey, and no longer are obedient
to parents and parents-in-law on that issue. They are more likely
to discuss it with their husbands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Regulation to Standardize Job Switching </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Municipal lawmakers passed a
regulation Thursday that will limit job-switching by people in
certain types of work.
</P>
<P>
The regulation will affect people in Beijing who have access to
national secrets and those who are in control of specialized
technology, business secrets or intellectual property rights
considered vital to the country, the department or the work unit
that hires them. The law becomes effective Jan 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
"Such people will face punishment if they quit jobs without
informing their employers or cause losses to their original
employers by disclosing business or technological secrets, or by
infringing on their intellectual property rights," the regulation
states. Serious violators may be brought to court.
</P>
<P>
The regulation also bans recruiters from hiring such people
and a fine of 10,000 yuan to 50,000 yuan may be imposed on
violators.
</P>
<P>
As the country moves toward a market economy, the old
life-long employment system is breaking down. People have the
right to choose jobs in their best interests. Last year alone,
60,000 people in Beijing switched jobs.
</P>
<P>
"The regulation is to standardize the personnel market, not to
discourage the normal flow of personnel," said one local
official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
