<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Govt to Resolve Land Imbalance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe has said the government will not hesitate to change the
constitution in its endeavors to give land to the landless black
people.
</P>
<P>
The government and the ruling ZANU (PF) are so determined to
give the people their soil that no statute would stop it from
doing so, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Forget what the constitution says. If it does not indicate
that we can take the land, then it will be changed and people
will just have to take the land," said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
He was addressing yesterday the Mashonaland East party
provincial leadership, heads of government departments,
traditional chiefs and other authorities in his ongoing
consultative meetings in Marondera of east Zimbabwe to assess the
land acquisition and distribution program.
</P>
<P>
He said, "the time has now come to call the soil of Zimbabwe
our soil because we are the sons of this soil."
</P>
<P>
Mugabe reiterated that political power should be matched with
economic gains, adding that it is folly to think that all is well
among blacks when only a minority group is sitting on most of the
land.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would never pay compensation to farmers
as this is tantamount to paying somebody who would have stolen
from you in order to get back one's stolen property.
</P>
<P>
The land was taken willy-nilly and thousands of black
Zimbabweans sacrificed their lives to win it back and yet the
government has never asked for compensation for the injuries and
losses of life suffered during the war of liberation, he said.
</P>
<P>
National Chairman of the Land Acquisition Committee Joseph
Msika stressed that the land is definitely going to be taken
before the end of the year and it is up to the people to make
full use of it.
</P>
<P>
"I know that in the 1940s most whites got huge tracts of land
and were given soft loans and we will do the same. We want a
back-up program and remove the monopoly which is in the hands of
the whites," said Msika.
</P>
<P>
Msika added, "this should be a land acquisition revolution and
we want everyone to be involved."
</P>
<P>
At least 62,000 families have been resettled since
independence but another 100,000 still wait for the land which
the government has been promising for the past 17 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
