<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Wushu Sets Sights Upon Olympic Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Japan's judo has entered the
Olympic Games, South Korea's Taekwondo will be there in 2000. How
about China's Wushu, also named martial art?
</P>
<P>
Dated back earlier than the ancient Olympic Games, the Chinese
traditional sport is eager to find its way to become a full
Olympic medal event.
</P>
<P>
In its campaign, China has been putting tremendous efforts as
Wushu is left as the lone non-Olympic sport in the on-going Eighth
National Games where all the others were cut off in its bold
Olympic-oriented reform.
</P>
<P>
And golds in the sport are increased to 15 from seven in the
Seventh National Games four years ago.
</P>
<P>
Some 77 member countries have joined their ranks in the
International Wushu Federation (IWF), which was founded in 1990
and chaired by Wu Shaozu, also minister of the Chinese State
Physical Culture and Sports Commission.
</P>
<P>
"The number of the membership has met the requirements of the
International Olympic Committee (IOC) for a full status in the
Olympic Games," said Zhang Shan, chairman of the arbitration
committee of the National Games Wushu competition.
</P>
<P>
The IWF will take concrete actions on its application in the
coming fourth World Wushu Championships slated late this month in
Rome, Italy.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch here on
Tuesday, minister Wu hoped Samaranch consider IWF's request during
the Championships.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, we'll take it into consideration," said Samaranch, who
was invited by Chinese Olympic Committee for the National Games
opened on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Wushu made its debut in an international meet as a formal event
at the 11th Asain Games held in Beijing in 1990, with the
participation of 96 players from 11 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
"The 11th Asian Games marked a breakthrough for Wushu, heading
towards Asia and the world," said Li Jie, president of the Chinese
Wushu Federation.
</P>
<P>
Col Giuseppe Falconi, president of the Italian Wushu
Federation, had expressed his firm support for IWF's application
when the bidding campaign for the 2004 Olympic Games was in full
swing.
</P>
<P>
"If Rome won the rights to host the 2004 Games, we would try
our best to list Wushu as a full event, at least as an exhibition
event," said Falconi, also chairman of the Organizing Committee
for the Fourth World Wushu Championships.
</P>
<P>
"It's only a matter of time for Wushu to enter the Olympic
family," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Rome championships will be the largest-ever Wushu meet in
history. At least 55 countries and regions will send some 700
competitiors to fight for 25 golds.
</P>
<P>
To usher in Wushu upon the Olympic stage, Falconi, who also
practises Wushu by playing shadow boxing, said he will invite IOC
chief Samaranch to attend the championships.
</P>
<P>
But the difficulties cannot be down-played in the course of
pushing the fledging world sport to the international arena.
</P>
<P>
The biggest obstacle is the lack of standard regulations in
ruling the competitions as gymnastics, judo and taekwando, which
poses the great challenge and remains as an unshakable task for us
in bringing the sport towards the Olympic Games, Li Jie said.
</P>
<P>
"I'm confident of materializing our dreams as Wushu is not only
a popular sport in China, but also a promosing sport that has been
winning more and more enthusiasts abroad," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
