<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slowdown Envisaged in Malaysia's Economic Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's economic
expansion in 1998 is clearly indicated to slow down due to an
envisaged slower pace of economic activities in the second half of
1997 following the volatility in its foreign exchange and stock
markets.
</P>
<P>
For 1998, its real gross domestic product (GDP) growth is
expected to grow at a moderate range of 7 percent against the
envisaged 8 percent in 1997 and 8.6 percent in 1996, according to
the Economic Report 1997/98 released here today by the Malaysian
Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
A slower growth in nominal gross national product (GNP) of 8.3
percent in current prices in 1998 is envisaged against the
projected 10.2 percent in 1997 and 14.3 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Malaysia's per capita income in
current prices is envisaged to increase by 5.7 percent in 1998
compared with estimated 7.7 percent in 1997 and 11.7 percent in
1996, to 12,797 ringgit from estimated 12,102 ringgit in 1997 and
11,239 ringgit in 1996 (about 3.2 ringgit = 1 U.S. dollar at the
current rate).
</P>
<P>
The moderation in real output growth of the economy in 1998
reflects largely the impact of a moderate expansion in the volume
of world trade, slower growth in domestic demand and income, as
well as a significant negative turnaround in the output of
agriculture sector from a growth of 3.5 percent in 1997 to a
decline of 1.2 percent in 1998, it said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has not been spared from the contagion effects of
developments in Thailand which have triggered volatility in the
region's financial markets, with its currency -- the ringgit --
depreciating by nearly 30 percent against the U.S. dollar since
July and stock prices dropped by some 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Output expansion in the manufacturing sector, the backbone of
the economy, is envisaged to slow down to a 10.5 percent increase
in 1998 against 12 percent in 1997, however the expansion remains
still strong.
</P>
<P>
With the manufacturing sector envisaged to expand at a rate
surpassing that of other sectors of the economy, its share to GDP
is expected to increase to 36.6 percent in 1998 against 35.5
percent in 1997 and 34.2 percent in 1996, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Construction starts in 1998 are expected to slow down with the
value-added of the construction sector to increase by 9 percent
against a projected growth of 11 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In line with the moderation in the growth of the primary and
secondary sectors of the economy, the report said the pace of
value-added of the services sector is expected to moderate
slightly to 8.6 percent in 1998 against 8.7 percent in 1997 with
its shares to GDP forecast to increase to 45.7 percent in the
coming year from 45 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Encouragingly, Malaysia's current account of the balance of
payments is envisaged to record a smaller deficit of 11.3 billion
ringgit against an estimated deficit of 13.1 billion ringgit in
1997, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The current account deficit is forecast to narrow from 5
percent of GNP in 1997 to 4 percent of GNP in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, inflation is likely to remain low, the report said
without giving specific rate of inflation.
</P>
<P>
It said with further measures to be announced in the 1998
Budget, the fundamentals of the economy would be strengthened
further. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
