<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UTC Success Attributed to Adapting to Chinese Culture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 17 (Xinhua) -- "When in Rome, do as the Romans
do." That philosophy has guided United Technologies Corp.'s
business in China, according to Richard Latham, president of UTC's
International Operation China.
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview with Xinhua, Latham outlined UTC's
approach: "We have to get fit in the Chinese culture and society,
let the Chinese do their way, use the Chinese way of saying
things, and use examples from the Chinese history in modern
management."
</P>
<P>
This thinking has played an important role in UTC's success in
China, he said. UTC is one of the world's largest industrial
conglomerates with holdings in aerospace equipment, machinery and
electrical products.
</P>
<P>
In China, UTC has 22 joint ventures and cooperative enterprises
in operation and 10 joint projects under negotiation in such
diverse product fields as aerospace engines, air conditioners,
elevators, auto parts and combustion turbines for industrial use.
</P>
<P>
Six UTC-funded ventures are under way in central and western
China, relatively backward areas rich in natural resources. Five
of the next ten joint ventures will be in that same part of China.
</P>
<P>
UTC generated 24 billion U.S. dollars in revenue in 1996, one
billion of which was related to China in foreign trade and
domestic sales. Latham said China is UTC's market with the fastest
growth.
</P>
<P>
Latham, an American who studied in the Beijing University 16
years ago, said mutual understanding between the United States and
China is inadequate.
</P>
<P>
"Culture is like an egg." Latham said, "You get through a layer
and you learn a little more about the egg, and you learn a little
more about the culture.
</P>
<P>
"The problem is most people never get beyond 'the shell of the
egg'," Latham said, in commenting on cultural misunderstanding
which he views as harmful to smooth economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Latham said that foreigners who work for UTC here are required
to have information for staff members interpreted or translated
into Chinese. He also said that Chinese workers are promoted to
management when qualified.
</P>
<P>
"They are hardworking and very well educated," Latham said of
his Chinese work force. Latham also praised UTC's Chinese
employees for their work ethic.
</P>
<P>
Chinese employees of UTC's subsidiary in Shanghai, Carrier,
have traveled to other joint ventures in Asia to train workers to
improve product quality.
</P>
<P>
The 25 percent share of the Chinese market attained by UTC's
Otis Elevator subsidiary can be traced to the leadership of Huang
Xiong, Latham said. Huang is president of Tianjin Otis.
</P>
<P>
Twenty investment analysts visited China in September with
George David, UTC chairman. UTC's subsequent three-point stock
gain on the New York Stock Exchange was attributed by Latham to
the analysts' "favorable assessment" of the work discipline,
education level of Chinese workers and the quality of both the
products and Chinese management.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
