<HEADLINE> Water Projects Play Key Role in Fighting Droughts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Water conservation projects in
northeast China's Liaoning Province are playing a crucial role in
the anti-drought drive, according to sources at the provincial
water conservancy department.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning has been enduring unusually dry weather since spring,
a condition that is threatening more than 1.3 million hectares of
farm land.
</P>
<P>
Emergency water conservation measures have been taken to
minimize losses. A fund of 200 million yuan has been established
to deal with the water shortage.
</P>
<P>
One system consisting of six reservoirs in the center region of
the province has guaranteed water-supply for the major irrigated
fields.
</P>
<P>
About 730,000 hectares of irrigated fields in the region should
have enough water to increase grain production by more than 500
million kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Twenty million cubic meters of water has also been diverted
from a northern reservoir to a grain base in the southern delta to
alleviate the water shortage.
</P>
<P>
These efforts are expected to raise the total output of 160,000
hectares of wheat fields in the province by more than 100 million
kilograms, officials said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, water-saving irrigation technology has been
implemented to decrease consumption.
</P>
<P>
More than 10,000 wells and ponds also have been dug or dredged,
providing water for 44,667 hectares of grain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
