<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Economic Growth Remains High in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's economic growth
for 1997 is expected to remain high although at a lower rate
compared with that in 1996 despite its economy was affected by
speculative attacks on the regional financial markets.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's real gross domestic product (GDP) growth is expected
to moderate to 8 percent in 1997 against 8.6 percent in 1996,
according to the Economic Report 1997/98 released here today by
the Malaysian Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
1997 is the 10th year for Malaysia to achieve economic growth
at a rate above 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Nominal gross national product (GNP) is envisaged to grow at a
rate of 10.2 percent in 1997 against that of 14.3 percent in 1996
while per capita income in current prices is estimated to increase
by 7.7 percent in 1997, against 11.7 percent in 1996, to 12,102
ringgit against 11,239 ringgit in 1996 (about 3.2 ringgit = 1 U.S.
dollar at the current rate), according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report said the moderation in output growth is mainly due
to an envisaged slower pace of economic activities in the second
half of the year.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has not been spared from the contagion effects of
developments in Thailand which have triggered volatility in the
region's financial markets, with its currency -- the ringgit --
depreciating by nearly 30 percent against the U.S. dollar since
July and stock prices dropped by some 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia was successful in keep inflation at a low level, which
eased during the first nine month of 1997 to 2.6 percent, the
lowest since 1990, against 3.6 percent during the corresponding
period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
For 1997 as a whole, the inflation rate would be around 3
percent as the country replenishes its stocks of supplies for the
remaining months of the year with imports at higher prices from
countries whose currencies have recently appreciated against the
ringgit, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the output performance of most sectors of the economy
remains strong, with the manufacturing, construction and some
sub-sectors in the services sector continuing to record
double-digit rates of expansion, it said.
</P>
<P>
Value-added in the manufacturing sector is envisaged to
increase by 12 percent in real terms with its share to the real
GDP expected to increase to 35.5 percent in the year against that
of 34.2 percent in 1996, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Though imposition of the limit on bank lending to the broad
property sector and the moderation in demand for properties are
expected to discourage new construction starts, value-added in the
construction sector is expected to grow by 11 percent in 1997 and
the share of the sector to GDP is expected to increase to 4.8
percent from 4.7 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Output growth of the agriculture, forestry, livestock and
fishery sector is envisaged pick up to 3.5 percent from 2.2
percent in 1996, the report said, adding that its share to GDP is
expected to continue to slide to 12.2 percent in 1997 from 12.7
percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The output growth in the mining sector is envisaged to slow
down to 2.8 percent in the year from 4.5 percent in 1996 with its
shares to GDP to decline further to 6.8 percent from 7.2 percent
during the same period, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It said that growth in value-added of the services sector is
expected to remain strong, although at a slower rate of 8.7
percent in 1997 against 9.7 percent in 1996 and the shares of
services sector to total GDP is estimated to increase to 45
percent against 44.8 percent in 1996,
</P>
<P>
The current account of the balance of payments is estimated to
record a slightly larger deficit of 13.1 billion ringgit in 1997,
compared with 12.3 billion ringgit in 1996, it said, adding the
current account deficit is envisaged to narrow to 5 percent of
GNP, against 5.2 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The current account deficit is expected to be adequately
financed by net inflow of foreign corporate direct investment,
amounting to 13.2 billion ringgit, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Given the contagion effects of the recent financial volatility,
Malaysia's economy is, however, projected to slow down to a growth
rate of 7 percent in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
