<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Statue of John Rabe Unveiled in East China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The Nanjing Office of
Germany-based Siemens held a ceremony on Thursday to unveil a
bronze statue of John Rabe, a German national who helped Chinese
refugees during the Rape of Nanjing in 1937.
</P>
<P>
The bronze statue, which measures 1.6 m in height, sits in
front of the Siemens Office in Nanjing, capital of east China's
Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
The statue also depicts medals Rabe received from the Chinese
government and the International Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
"Rabe recorded the details of the Rape of Nanjing and collected
historical relics from the period," according to Siemens
Vice-President Ender.
</P>
<P>
"The deeds exhibited his true courage and sympathy," said Ender.
</P>
<P>
Ursula Reinhardt, Rabe's granddaughter, attended the ceremony
together with Wang Shu, president of the Sino-German Friendship
Association, and He Zehui, an academician from the Chinese Academy
of Sciences who personally viewed Rabe's diary while in Germany.
</P>
</TEXT>
