<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Host ASEAN Standing Committee Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The first meeting of the 31st
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) Standing Committee (ASC) will be
held here on October 21 to 23, the Philippine News Agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will discuss the issues arising from the last ASEAN
Ministerial and Post Ministerial Meetings in Kuala Lumpur last
July, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Foreign Affairs Department said one of the
proposals which the upcoming meeting will consider is an ASEAN
roundtable conference on Legal, Technical and Economic Issues on
Multimedia Technology.
</P>
<P>
The roundtable conference was originally scheduled to be held
in Kuala Lumpur also later this month.
</P>
<P>
The ASC meeting will also focus on the latest developments on
ASEAN cooperation in functional areas. Earlier, ASEAN leaders have
decided to elevate functional cooperation to a higher plane "to
bring about shared prosperity" to all ASEAN member countries.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN has already established an award system to formally
recognize individuals and organizations which have made
significant contributions to ASEAN functional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The first awardees will be honored at the next ASEAN Formal
Summit in Hanoi, Vietnam in 1998, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Among the other agenda items in the meeting are the
consideration of the reports of its subsidiary bodies -- the ASEAN
Senior Officials Meeting on Drugs, the ASEAN Senior Officials
Meeting on the Environment and the ASEAN Committee on Social
Development.
</P>
<P>
The ASC meeting will also include a briefing on the
preparations for the ASEAN Informal Summit scheduled on December
14-16 in Kuala Lumpur, and the preparations for the 31st ASEAN
Ministerial Meeting set on July 21-29, 1998 in Manila.
</P>
<P>
Likewise tabled for discussion in next week's meeting are
progress reports on ASEAN development cooperation with its
dialogue partners.
</P>
<P>
As current ASEAN chairman, the Philippines also chairs the ASC,
the committee in charge of coordinating and directing the
implementation of all ASEAN programs and activities.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN presently groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia,
Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Its dialogue partners include Australia, Canada, China,
European Union, India, South Korea, New Zealand, Russia, the
United States and the United Nations Development Program.
</P>
<P>
Sectoral dialogue relations are currently being worked out,
under the Philippine chairmanship, between ASEAN and Pakistan.
</P>
</TEXT>
