<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diarrhoea Kills 56 Ugandan Children Everyday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Fifty-six Ugandan children die
of diarrhoea everyday as a result of poor sanitation, reported
local daily "The New Vision" today.
</P>
<P>
Josephine Nambooze, health consultant in the Health Ministry,
was quoted as saying that human excreta disposal in Uganda is
appalling and increasing the vicious cycle of sickness.
</P>
<P>
Opening a two-day seminar on sanitation here on Thursday,
Nambooze said that only 47.3 percent out of every 100 homes in
the country has latrines.
</P>
<P>
The situation, according to her, is grimmer in the northern
part of the country, where only four out of 100 homes have a
latrine.
</P>
<P>
Crispus Kiyonga, the health minister of Uganda, in his speech
disclosed that in Uganda 50 percent of out-patient cases are
sanitation related and the country spends 27 million U.S. Dollars
on their treatment, adding that some 10 million Dollars more are
lost in wasted work days.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Kintu Musoke in his opening speech at the
seminar urged the local leaders not to blame their fellow
villagers, instead sensitize them and be their examples. 
</P>
</TEXT>
