<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swazi Government Cuts S. African TV Broadcasts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The Swaziland government
has cut the TV broadcasts of South African Broadcasting
Corporation (SABC) to the people of the kingdom, South African
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the switch-off on Thursday was the Swazi
government's dissatisfaction with what it called the SABC's
one-sided coverage of this week's national strike, the SABC said.
</P>
<P>
A Swazi government spokesman accused the SABC of not depicting
the truth about the strike and said news pictures broadcast on
Monday night were filmed in February.
</P>
<P>
SABC denied the claims, saying that the footage and interviews
were done this week.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Swaziland prime minister's office, Meshack
Shongwe, said the Swazi government and general public were
surprised and shocked at the screening of "a distorted and
unbalanced view of the current situation" on SABC television.
</P>
<P>
SABC spokesman Enoch Sithole said Thursday that Swaziland's
decision to cut the SABC feed was unfortunate for people who
benefited from the South African broadcaster's service.
</P>
<P>
He said the political freedoms gained in South Africa should
be extended to the Swazi kingdom.
</P>
<P>
"People should be able to watch whatever they like, and make
up their own minds," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The nationwide strike called by the Swaziland Federation of
Trade Unions (SFTU) began Monday, but aborted when workers of
three major sugar companies returned to work on Tuesday and
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The SFTU was supported mainly by workers in the sugar industry
and plantation hands. Sugar is the kingdom's main foreign
currency generator. 
</P>
</TEXT>
