<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Trap, Skeet Added to 2000 Olympic Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The women's trap and skeet
shooting events were added to the agenda of the 2000 Olympic Games
but the number of sharpshooters were reduced to 310, a top Chinese
shooting official revealed here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made by the International Olympic Committee
(IOC) on May 21 when the IOC finally ratified the application of
the International Shooting Federation.
</P>
<P>
However, the number of sharpshooters were reduced from 330 in
Atlanta to 310 in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Gong Liren, chief of the Chinese Shooting and Archery Sports
Center, said the IOC has made the right decision which manifests
the equality between the men and women shooters.
</P>
<P>
China once enjoyed its upperhands in these two women events as
Zhang Shan of Sichuan province beat her men opponents to take the
title of the men's skeet in the Barcelona Games, Gong said.
</P>
<P>
However, women sharpshooters have been prevented from competing
in the men's trap and skeet events after the Barcelona Games, and
many a countries had re-adjusted their Olympic-oriented strategies
to focus on the lone event of the women's double trap, including
China.
</P>
<P>
"Thus, we had lost our advantages in the events wherein Italy,
Russia and Finland have been keeping their trainings," Gong said.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Shan has not trained in her discipline of skeet for
years, and it's hard for her and her teamates to back to their top
forms in a short period of time after a hiatus of years, the
Chinese shooting officials lamented.
</P>
<P>
"However, we also have a few young sharpshooters of great
potential, including Chen Zhengru of Sichuan province, who once
shot 123 points which overpassed the world record of 119," Gong
Said.
</P>
<P>
While the women shooters of Italy, Russia and Finland will
become top favorites to win the trap and skeet events in Sydney,
China also has its medal hopefuls upon their perfomances there, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. to Extend Massive Poverty Alleviation Loan to Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) announced today that competent
U.N. agencies will extend a massive loan of 20 million
U.S. dollars to Romania for alleviating poverty in the country.
</P>
<P>
Leueen Miller, the UNDP representative to Romania, made the
announcement at the inauguration of a UNDP-sponsored "poverty
elimination week" in Bucharest, the Romanian capital.
</P>
<P>
Miller said the loan will be effective between 1997 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
In an address to the inaugural ceremony of the poverty
elimination week, Romanian President Emil Constantinescu vowed to
do his best to ensure a good life through reforms for the people.
</P>
<P>
Constantinescu admitted Romania is facing a serious social
problem -- many people are living in poverty. To cover up the
fact is to be guilty of sustaining and deepening the problem, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We have to admit the fact in an effort to make it a priority
for the everyday work of the government, parliament and
president," the president said.
</P>
<P>
The president noted that the Romanian government has taken
several measures to improve the situation including offering
living subsidies to poor families with many children, providing
stipends to high school and elementary school students and
improving pensions for farmers. But he also said those are not
enough.
</P>
<P>
Information distributed by the UNDP at a news conference
following the opening ceremony indicated that about 38 percent of
Romanians are living in poverty and 7 percent are unable to
maintain a normal life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
