<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poland Reports Rapid Development of Telecommunications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Polish telecommunications
industry has developed rapidly in recent years, with a marked
increase in the number of telephone subscribers, Minister of Posts
and Telecommunications Andrzej Zielinski said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Zielinski said that the current 7
million telephone subscribers nationwide represent a noteworthy
increase over the country's total of 3 million in 1990 and 4.5
million in 1993.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this year, the total number of phone subscribers
nationwide is expected to hit 7.5 million.
</P>
<P>
In terms of phone subscribers, one in every 100 Poles possess
20 telephone sets today as compared with 11 in 1993.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, 30 percent of the country's population will
have access to telephone service, reaching the average level in
Europe. This figure is expected to double by 2005, about the
current level in developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, cellular phones are being popularized nationwide.
The total number of cellular phones in use at present is 700,000,
seven times that two years ago.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the year, cellular phones in use are expected to
total 1 million, which will be further increased to 3 million by
2000.
</P>
<P>
The telecommunications industry enjoys an even higher growth
rate in rural areas, Zielinski said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Fighting Worst Oil Spill After Collision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Singapore is fighting its
worst oil spill in the region following a collision between a very
large crude carrier (VLCC) and an oil tanker Wednesday night just
off the Singapore port limits in the Singapore Strait.
</P>
<P>
The local press reported today that a massive cleanup operation
is now under way with a fleet of 34 anti-pollution craft being
called in to try to contain the oil spill and prevent it from
reaching the shores of the tourist attraction island of Sentosa
and Singapore island proper.
</P>
<P>
The Maritime and Port Authority of Singapore (MPA) raised last
night its estimate of the amount of oil spillage to 25,000 tons,
up from the previous estimation of 3,000 to 4,000 tons earlier in
the day.
</P>
<P>
The MPA has also called in resources of the Singapore Armed
Forces and made an appeal to Australia, Japan and the United
States for more equipment to help speed up the cleanup process.
</P>
<P>
An MPA spokesman told local newspapers that there are no plans
to close the shipping lanes in the Singapore Strait, one of the
world's most congested routes and that the "situation was under
control."
</P>
<P>
The collision occurred between an empty VLCC and an oil tanker
at about 9 p.m. Wednesday night. It took place just off the
Singapore port limits, where visibility then was about eight
kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The Thai-registered VLCC "Orapin Global" of 129,702 gross tons
was transiting the Singapore Strait from east to west while the
Cyprus-flagged oil tanker "Evoikos," 75,428 gross tons, was
eastward-bound for Singapore from the United Arab Emirates, when
they were both warned of the impending collision by the Vessel
Traffic Information Service, the MPA said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The MPA said Evoikos was carrying about 120,000 tons of marine
fuel oil when the collision took place.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAO Leader Appeals for More Investment in Food Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 16 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO) today called on all countries in the world,
especially the poorer developing countries, to attach great
importance to more investment in food security.
</P>
<P>
FAO Direct General Jacques Diouf made this appeal in his
inaugural speech at the World Food Day ceremony held on the theme
"Investing in Food Security."
</P>
<P>
"If the goal of food security for all is reached, there must be
significant increase in food production and improved access to
food," Diouf said.
</P>
<P>
However, the director general also noted that much of the
investment in food security in poorer countries would continue to
be private, with three-quarters coming from millions of small
farmers, traders, village artisans, businessmen and others engaged
in the production and distribution of food in the poorer countries.
</P>
<P>
"The remaining one-quarter of investment, some 41 million
dollars each year, will consist of public investments to create
and maintain the conditions for profitable private-sector
activities," he added.
</P>
<P>
If bilateral and multilateral support remain at the same level
as in the past, some 15 billion U.S. dollars will be needed
annually to help the poorest countries meet the requirement of
investment in food security, said the FAO director general.
</P>
<P>
Diouf said Africa is a special area in which the encouragement
of cooperation is urgently needed and where development can set in
motion "the economic and political progress necessary for
eradicating poverty, famine and alienation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Bank To Provide Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The Export-Import Bank of the
United States has signed an agreement with the Bank of China to
provide 60 million US dollars in loan for the Shanghai Metro Corp,
today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be used to buy a signal and control system, an
automatic fare collection system, a fire alarm and suppression
system and engineering services from a number of US firms. The
equipment will be shipped and installed over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
The US Department of Commerce estimated that the loan will
support more than 1,200 jobs directly and indirectly in the United
States, the newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
