<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Olympic Organizer Criticizes Ski Federation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Japan's winter Olympic organizer
criticized the International Ski Federation of using the press to
intimidate Japan in a dispute over the length of the men's
downhill ski course for the 1988 Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Asahi Evening News, Makoto Kobayashi,
director general of the Nagano Olympic Committee, said: "I want
people to understand our feeling. FIS is always intimidating us."
</P>
<P>
The International Ski Federation has repeatedly said the
current course falls short of Olympic standards. Japan's
organizing committee has insisted that it cannot be lengthened
without encroaching on protected national park land.
</P>
<P>
Kobayashi said that FIS President Marc Hodler tried last month
to sell a plan for extending the course to the media before even
consulting Japanese organizers.
</P>
<P>
The men's downhill will be one of the marquee events of the
February 7-22 games and the course has been criticized as too easy
for top international competition. The ski federation and the
International Olympic Committee want the start raised to an
elevation of 1,800 meters, from its current 1,680 meters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
