<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reiterates Policies on Control Over Nuclear Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- To prevent the widespread
proliferation of weapons of mass destruction, especially nuclear
weapons, is an important component of China's independent foreign
policy of peace, a senior Chinese official said today.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Li Changhe of the Chinese Permanent Mission in
Vienna made the remark at today's meeting of the Zangger
Committee. During the meeting, China was accepted for the first
time as a full member of the organization.
</P>
<P>
"The prevention of nuclear proliferation is a long and arduous
task that calls for the joint efforts of the international
community," Li said, adding, "The Chinese government is ready to
make unremitting efforts with other countries for the common
development of both nuclear non-proliferation and peaceful use of
nuclear energy."
</P>
<P>
However, he emphasized that the prevention of nuclear
proliferation should in no way affect or hinder the normal nuclear
cooperation for peaceful use among various countries, let alone be
used as an excuse for discrimination or an application of willful
sanctions against developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The Vienna-based Zangger Committee, founded in 1971, is the
first international organization formed on control over nuclear
technology.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the committee, which groups 33 nuclear or
nuclear-related export countries, is to strengthen consultation
and cooperation on issues of nuclear non-proliferation and export
control under the principles of the Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT).
</P>
<P>
"China adheres to the policy that it will not advocate,
encourage or engage in the proliferation of nuclear weapons, nor
assist other countries in developing nuclear weapons," Li said.
</P>
<P>
He added that for many years the Chinese government has
exercised strict and effective control over nuclear and
nuclear-related exports, including exchanges of personnel and
information.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the three principles of China's nuclear policy,
which are to serve peaceful purposes only, to accept IAEA
safeguards and to forbid the transfer of technology to any third
country without China's consent.
</P>
<P>
Li also briefed the meeting on the Circular on Strict
Implementation of China's Nuclear Export Policy and the
Regulations on Nuclear Export Control the Chinese government
promulgated in May and September.
</P>
<P>
Under the circular, no agency or company is allowed to conduct
cooperation or exchange of personnel or technological data with
nuclear facilities not under IAEA safeguards.
</P>
<P>
The nuclear export control regulations established, in the form
of law, the three principles governing China's nuclear export, and
the policy of not providing assistance to nuclear facilities not
under IAEA safeguards.
</P>
<P>
The regulations provide that nuclear exports are monopolized by
units designated by the government and no other agency or
individual is allowed to engage in such exports.
</P>
<P>
Li added that relevant departments of China are stepping up
their efforts to complete the export-control regulations on the
nuclear-related dual use items. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Government Wins Confidence Vote in Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government won a vote
of confidence in the Senate today with 168 in favor and 64
against, including a surprise vote from ex-President Francesco
Cossiga.
</P>
<P>
The former president said his vote did not mean that he has
joined the center-left majority, but he sees Romano Prodi's
center-left coalition government as the clearest political
solution for the moment.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Refoundation Party forced Prodi to resign last
week when it refused to back a cost-cutting budget plan, which
contains 3 billion U.S. dollars in spending cuts, most from
pensions and other social benefits.
</P>
<P>
The government said the cuts are vital for Italy to join the
European Monetary Union.
</P>
<P>
A similar motion was carried earlier by the Lower House of
Parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
