<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fires on Rise in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Fires that have been ravaging
Indonesia's forests and brush for months are on the rise again,
despite intense efforts to combat them, the National Institute for
Flight and Aerospace (LAPAN) said today.
</P>
<P>
Satellite images detected at least 55 new fire spots between
late Wednesday and early Thursday, compared with only 21 on
Tuesday, according to a LAPAN report issued here.
</P>
<P>
The new fires were located in the regions of Sumatra,
Kalimantan, Sulawesi and Java.
</P>
<P>
The fires, which have devastated more than 300,000 hectares of
forest and bush and have covered other Southeast Asian nations
with smoky haze, have been declared a national natural disaster by
President Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
The government has revoked timber-use permits of 29 forest
companies for burning to clear land for plantations and has blamed
the El Nino whether phenomenon as the most instrumental factor
behind the worsening of the disaster.
</P>
<P>
But the Environmental Impact Management Agency has said only
heavy rainfall will help thousands of firefighters in their
struggle to extinguish the widespread fires.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a U.N. body said here that a rapid response is still
required to cope with forest fires in some areas in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Disaster Assessment and Coordination said that even
though the state of emergency appears to be over, the ongoing
peat, coal and surface fires continue to contribute to the
spreading haze.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Indonesian Forum for Environment (WALHI)
announced that it has despatched 105,250 respiratory masks to
Kalimantan and Sumatra where an estimated 20 million people are
faced with respiratory problems because of the haze.
</P>
<P>
WALHI estimated that at least 1.7 million hectares of forests
have been damaged by the fires, but "the number is also temporary
which can be revised after all fires have been put off."
</P>
<P>
WALHI also estimated the total financial loss due to the fires
and haze at 6.2 trillion rupiah (about 1.7 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The international community has up to date pledged cash
contributions to Indonesia valued at more than 1.5 million dollars
besides much material and technical assistance, official sources
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
