<HEADLINE> Norway's New PM Forms Coalition Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Norway's new prime minister
Kajell Magne Bondevik today announced the composition of a
three-party coalition government, according to news reports
reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The minority coalition, which came to power after the
resignation of Labor Prime Minister Thorbjoern Jagland on Monday,
consists of 19 ministers, nine from Bondevik's the Christian
Democratic Party, six from the Center Party and four from the
Liberal Party.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Center Party Anne Enger Lahnstein is named
culture minister and Chairman of the Liberal Party Lars Sponheim
trade and industry minister.
</P>
<P>
Knut Vollebaek and Dag Jostein Fjaervoll of the Christian
Democratic Party will hold the portfolios of finance and defense,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Nine of the 19 government ministers were women, keeping
Bondevik's promise that at least 40 percent of his cabinet would
be female.
</P>
<P>
The coalition has just 42 seats in the 165-seat parliament.
</P>
<P>
Jagland and his Labor government resigned due to a
disappointing result in September's national election. Labor won
65 seats in parliament, down from 67 in the 1993 national
election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
