<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile registered a 36.2 percent reduction in
produce exports during the season which just ended.
</P>
<P>
According to the figures, the 4.5 million boxes of produce
shipped up to August 31, 1996, dropped to 2.89 million boxes in
the same period this year, mainly due to a 49 percent drop in
onion shipments, compared with the previous period.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The United States was the biggest foreign
investor in Argentina, with a total of 12 billion dollars during
the 1990-1996 period, the Industry Ministry announced.
</P>
<P>
U.S. investments in the country will add up to 18 billion
dollars, 34.1 percent of the total foreign investments in the
country.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Nicaragua loses nearly 7 million dollars a year
because of the illegal transport of shrimp larvae to Honduras.
</P>
<P>
During the latest operation, the Nicaraguan Navy confiscated
about 10 million shrimp larvae from Honduran traffickers in
September.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The National Statistics Institute said that
unemployment in the urban zones of Uruguay increased from 11.8
percent to 12 percent between June and August, compared with the
previous three-month period.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate remained at 12.2 percent in this capital.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- The Costa Rican Foreign Trade Ministry said that
the exports of agricultural products jumped 5.5 percent during the
first eight months of 1997, compared with the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
The income in exports rose from 937 million dollars in
January-August 1996 to 988 million dollars in the same period this
year.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Central America exported 1.96 billion dollars
worth of coffee during the 1996-1997 harvest, a figure that
surpassed by 24.8 percent the previous agricultural cycle.
</P>
<P>
The Central American countries produced 15.8 million quintales
of coffee, during the 1996-1997 harvest, which began on October 1,
1996, and ended on September 30 this year, three percent more than
that in the previous cycle.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- The Colombian government approved its 1998
budget of 38,700 billion pesos (approximately 38.7 billion
dollars), 13.6 percent more than the budget authorized for this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
