<HEADLINE> Exports, Remittances to Cut Philippines' Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines expects a lower current account deficit this year with
the positive impact of the peso depreciation on exports and
increased remittances from overseas Filipino workers.
</P>
<P>
In an interview published here today, Central Bank Governor
Gabriel Singson said the current account situation for the second
half of this year will be better than the first with the
improvement in the trade deficit and an increase in remittances
over the next few months.
</P>
<P>
"Contrary to what has been projected for the end of this year,
the deficit should be somewhat smaller than last year's," the
governor said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the government projected a deficit of 4.1 billion U.S.
dollars for this year, or 4.2 percent of the gross domestic
product. The 1996 deficit was about 3.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The current account is the portion of the balance of payment
representing merchandise trade, income earned from investments
abroad, money paid to foreign investors and transactions on which
the government expects no returns.
</P>
<P>
During the first half of this year, the trade deficit declined
to 5.6 billion dollars from 6.1 billion registered a year ago
after exports increased by 22 percent and earnings from personal
income of Filipinos overseas workers grew by 17.9 percent to 3.2
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the remittances by Filipino overseas workers totaled
4.3 billion dollars. Philippine banks are projecting an increase
in the remittances of up to 20 percent in the second half of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Singson also expected higher receipts from the exports sector
in the second semester with the depreciation of the peso, which
has fallen by over 30 percent since July.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
