<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, October 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- The British government announced Thursday that it
would ban British political parties from accepting donations from
abroad and donations above 5,000 pounds (8,100 U.S. dollars) would
also have to be made public.
</P>
<P>
"This is another step towards greater openness and transparency
in public life and demonstrates our determination to remove an
unnecessary layer of secrecy and undue influence in our political
system," Home Secretary Jack Straw said. (UK-Foreign Donations)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- Former President Denis Sassou Nguesso of the Congo
Republic has declared victory in the four-month civil war and
promised to set up "a government of national union" in the coming
days.
</P>
<P>
He made the declaration Thursday after his troops captured the
capital city of Brazzaville and the oil port of Pointe-Noire.
(Congo Republic-Sassou-Victory)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl Thursday made clear that
if being re-elected in next year's general elections, he would
stay in office until 2002, denying rumors that he is considering
an early handover.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Germany ZDF television network, Kohl
said his candidacy for office in the 1998 elections was for the
full four-year term. "No chancellor would stand for part of it.
That would be the very last thing that I would do," he said.
(Germany-Kohl-Handover)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The British government Thursday announced that
Britain would spend almost 100 million pounds (about 160 million
U.S. dollars) on seven new missiles for its Trident nuclear
submarines in an effort to reinforce its nuclear deterrent force.
</P>
<P>
John Gilbert, Britain's minister for defense procurement, said
in a written statement to the House of Lords: "This will bring the
number of Trident missiles purchased or ordered by the UK to 58."
(UK-Missile-Order)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian main opposition, including the Russian
Communist Party, the Agrarians and the People's Power, on Thursday
approved a letter to President Boris Yeltsin, showing a way out of
the government "crisis", the Itar-Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
According to Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov, the letter
stressed that "it would be important to change an attitude to the
law on the government for a final decision to be taken on a
no-confidence vote in the government." (Russia-Opposition)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- The satellite broadcasting system will be launched
in Kenya next June and services will be fully operational by the
end of next year under an agreement signed here Thursday between
the Kenyan government and World Space Management Corporation
(WSMC).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony of the agreement, Johnstone
Makau, Kenyan Minister for Information and Broadcasting, said the
WSMC was the first international corporation to set up satellite
radio in Kenya. (Kenya-broadcasting)
</P>
<P>
