<HEADLINE> Tourism to Boost Ukrainian Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Tourism is the potential
cornerstone for economic recovery in the city of Kiev and the
Ukraine as well, said Vladimir Jalovy, the deputy mayor of Kiev.
</P>
<P>
He said today that Ukraine received 13.5 million tourists in
1996, including 11 million Ukrainians and 2.5 million
foreigners. Meanwhile, 3.2 million Ukrainians traveled abroad,
mostly in other former Soviet republics. In the past few years,
only about four million foreigners visited Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Jalovy said there are 673 travel agencies, one fourth of the
national total, located in the Ukrainian capital. The 21 hotels in
Kiev can accommodate 6,000 tourists a day and seven new hotels are
currently under construction.
</P>
<P>
The deputy mayor expects a tourism boom in 1998 when the
Council of Europe holds its annual meeting in the East European
country next May. He is also concerned that Ukraine's hotel
facilities cannot provide satisfactory services for those European
officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
