<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Menem Discuss Free Trade Area of Americas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, October 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton attended two working meetings today with his Argentine
counterparter Carlos Menem to discuss regional economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The two heads of state discussed topics on the Free Trade Area
of the Americas (FTAA) and the Southern Common Market (Mercosur).
</P>
<P>
Clinton arrived here Wednesday night for an official visit to
Argentina. He advocated the rapid creation of FTAA before the
year 2005, an idea he proposed at the Ibero-American Summit in
December 1994 in Miami, the United States.
</P>
<P>
Argentine Foreign Minister Guido di Tella said at a press
conference after the two presidential meetings that Clinton told
Menem that Mercosur and FTAA "do not exclude each other."
</P>
<P>
Mercosur, established in December 1994 to promote free trade in
the region, is the biggest trade bloc in South America. It groups
Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay, and has Chile and Bolivia
as associate members.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Menem discussed the concession by the United States
to Argentina of the Non-NATO ally status, which Clinton has
communicated to the U.S. Congress.
</P>
<P>
Di Tella said this status means that Argentina's relations with
the United States are good and many benefits will follow, such as
new confidence and investments in the country.
</P>
<P>
In their talks, the two presidents also discussed the issue of
the Malvinas (Falkland) Islands. Di Tella said that Argentina has
not asked the United States to mediate in the case, because
Argentina now has good relations with Britain and has made some
progress in recent dialogues.
</P>
<P>
These two meetings were the most important part of Clinton's
Argentine trip. The U.S. president will hold more informal chats
during his trip to the city of Bariloche on October 17-18.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will end his visit to Argentina on Sunday and return to
Washington immediately. His Latin American tour took him to
Venezuela and Brazil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
