<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Emission of Greenhouse Gases on Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Canada's emission of greenhouse
gases has been on the rise instead of going down as it promised
five years ago at the Rio Earth Summit, according to new data made
public today.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, Canada signed the international climate-change
convention and pledged to stabilize its emissions of greenhouse
gases at 1990 levels by the year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, the country's emission of carbon dioxide has
actually risen more than 10.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
For all greenhouse gases, including carbon dioxide, the
increase is between 12.6 to 13.7 percent, according to data from
Canada's Environmental Department.
</P>
<P>
This shows that Canada's strategy of voluntary reductions by
industry is not working, said Louise Comeau of the Sierra Club of
Canada.
</P>
<P>
"Emissions can come down if Canada does something about
it... Voluntary programs don't cut it," she told a news conference
here today.
</P>
<P>
But the government doesn't seem to be interested in plans other
than voluntary programs.
</P>
<P>
The government is said to be under heavy pressure from energy
producers not to go too far in Kyoto, Japan, where countries that
signed the Rio treaty will meet in December to negotiate binding
targets beyond 2000.
</P>
<P>
"The targets have to be realistic, realizable," insisted a
spokesman from Canada's Natural Resources Department.
</P>
<P>
It has been widely acknowledged that rising concentrations of
greenhouse gases in the atmosphere threaten to warm the global
climate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
