</P>
<P>
-- The daily frontpaged an editorial, calling for a governing
by law and socialist democracy.
</P>
<P>
The editorial, entitled "Making Great Efforts to Accelerate the
Process of Governing by Law," quotes President Jiang Zemin's
report to the 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of
China as saying, governing by law is the fundamental principle of
the party in leading the people and administering the country.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin met in Shanghai yesterday with
Henry Muller, editorial editor of the Time Inc. of the United
States and was interviewed by correspondents from the weekly news
magazine.
</P>
<P>
Jiang briefed the US journalists on the significance of his
upcoming state visit to the US, and answered their questions about
Sino-US relations, China's economic situation, the reform of
China's state-owned enterprises and some other issues.
</P>
<P>
 Xinhua Daily Telegraph
</P>
<P>
-- The 15th World Petroleum Congress closed in Beijing
yesterday after five days of intensive discussions on prospects of
the world energy industry.
</P>
<P>
More than 5,000 officials, senior managers and researchers
exchanged views on major issues concerning future trends of the
petroleum industry during the congress.
</P>
<P>
-- The Information Office of the State Council yesterday issued
a White Paper on Freedom of Religious Belief in China.
</P>
<P>
The white paper, with more than 10,000 Chinese characters,
consists of five parts: the present conditions of religion in
China, legal protection of the freedom of religious belief,
judicial and administrative guarantees and supervision of the
freedom of religious belief, support for independence and
initiative in management of religious affairs and protection of
the right to freedom of religious belief for ethnic minorities.
</P>
<P>
 China Daily
</P>
<P>
-- The Chinese government held an assembly yesterday to
celebrate World Food Day in Dalian, a coastal city in northeast
China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
China has managed to support its population, 22 percent of the
world total, with a mere 7 percent of the world's arable land, a
Ministry of Agriculture official said at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese exports soared while imports registered a rapid
increase during the first three quarters this year, according to a
report from the General Administration of Customs.  
</P>
