<HEADLINE> South China City Attracts Japanese Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, capital of south
China's Guangdong Province, has become a popular investment site
for Japanese with a capital outlay exceeding 400 million
U.S. dollars, according to the local statistics bureau.
</P>
<P>
Japanese investment ranks sixth among all overseas investments
in Guangzhou, an economic center in southern China.
</P>
<P>
Many big Japanese companies and consortiums have invested in
Guangzhou in such sectors as chemicals, machinery, electronics,
automobiles and metallurgy.
</P>
<P>
Investments include the Guangzhou Pacific Tinplate Co. Ltd.,
receiving 90 million U.S. dollars from Japan; the Guangzhou Asian
American Polyester Co. Ltd., 60 million U.S. dollars; and the
Guangzhou Hitachi Co., 60 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Chen Kaizhi, Guangzhou's vice-mayor, told Xinhua in a recent
interview that the economic and technological cooperation between
Guangzhou and Japan has resulted in broad-based economic success.
</P>
<P>
Chen said the city is encouraging more Japanese investment in
such sectors as urban infrastructures and high-technology
industries.  
</P>
