<HEADLINE> Former World Champion Comes Back With New Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 16 (Xinhua) -- After a year-long battle with
testicular cancer, former world cycling champion Lance Armstrong
of United States was ready to return to competition with United
States Postal Service Pro Cycling Team.
</P>
<P>
The America's best-known cyclist was diagnosed with testicular
cancer that had already spread to his lungs and brain last
October. Then Armstrong went through extensive chemotherapy and
had two operations.
</P>
<P>
Armstong had a 1.2 million U.S. dollars a year contract with
the French team Cofidis before being stricken with cancer. Cofidis
dropped him earlier this month. The terms of the new contract were
not announced, but it was said that it was for much less money.
</P>
<P>
The two-time Tour de France winner and two-time Olympian said
his comeback was just a try and he had no design to win any
races. He had been training seriously since October.
</P>
<P>
Armstrong will return to professional cycling at the Redlands
Classic in Redlands, California, on March 3-8. He will join the
team's annual training camp in Southern California in
mid-January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
