<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Urges Immediate End to Hostilities in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of
the United Nations today adopted a resolution, calling for an
immediate end to all hostilities in the Republic of the Congo.
</P>
<P>
In the resolution, the Security Council expressed deep concern
over the grave situation and deplored the loss of life and the
deteriorating humanitarian situation in the country. It called on
all parties to ensure the safety of the civilian population and
the safe and unrestricted delivery of humanitarian assistance.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council called upon all states in the region to
support a peaceful resolution of the conflict and to avoid any
actions which could exacerbate the situation.
</P>
<P>
It condemned all external interference in the country,
including the intervention of foreign forces, in violation of the
Charter of the United Nations, and called for the immediate
withdrawal of all foreign forces including mercenaries.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council reiterated the importance of a political
settlement and national reconciliation and called upon the parties
to cooperate with the International Mediation Committee chaired by
the President of Gabon and with the joint United
Nations/Organization of African Unity Special Envoy in reaching
rapid agreement on peaceful transition arrangements leading to the
holding of democratic and free and fair elections with the
participation of all parties.
</P>
<P>
The conflict in the Congo Republic began on June 5 when
President Pascal Lissoba's soldiers surrounded the Brazzaville
home of his rival, General Denis Sassou Nguesso, in a pre-election
crackdown on private militia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
