<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian State Oil Company Unveils Investment Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian state oil
company, Petrobras, has announced a plan for investment in the
national oil industry for the next three years that includes a
13.7-billion-U.S.-dollar outlay.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released by the local media today, Petrabaras
president Joel Renno said that Petrobras will allow 88 percent of
the country's oil fields to be exploited by private companies.
</P>
<P>
Renno said that 63 national and foreign private enterprises
have confirmed their interest in developing projects associated to
Petrobras.
</P>
<P>
Under the investment plant, Petrobras will reach by the year
2000 an average daily oil output of 1.5 million barrels and an
average daily natural gas output of 50 million cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Brazil produced last year 900,000 barrels of oil a day.
</P>
</TEXT>
