<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Survey Finds Sharp Drop in Aid to Poor Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Aid from the world's richest
nations to the world's poorest has dropped to its lowest level
since such records have been kept, according to a U.S. survey
released today.
</P>
<P>
A report released by InterAction, an association of 158 U.S.
voluntary groups, said that the U.S. is the stingiest in terms of
the proportion of total wealth it donates.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., which devotes 0.12 percent of its GNP to foreign aid,
was at the bottom of the "generosity league," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Government aid by the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development (OECD), which groups the world's 21 wealthiest
countries, fell by 3.8 billion U.S. dollars in 1996, when it
totaled 55.8 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The figure, representing 0.25 percent of their combined gross
national product last year, is the lowest since statistics began
in 1950, InterAction said.
</P>
<P>
"Most donors are failing abjectly to live up to the (aid)
targets they have set themselves," said the report.
</P>
<P>
The OECD has a longstanding target for its members to devote
0.7 percent of GNP to ending world poverty. Currently, only
Denmark, Norway, Sweden, and the Netherlands are meeting that
goal.
</P>
<P>
Most of the world's richest nations have demonstrated a total
lack of commitment to reach the OECD goal.
</P>
<P>
Some 1.3 billion people worldwide live in absolute poverty,
according to a World Bank estimate, which includes all those who
live on less than one U.S. dollar a day.
</P>
<P>
The world's largest aid donor is Japan, followed by the United
States, Germany, and France. They account for 60 percent of all
overseas development assistance. All expect their aid to decline
in coming years, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> California Researchers Study Gun Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Researchers in California of
the United States say three of every four guns seized by police in
crimes committed in the state capital Sacramento are handguns,
predominantly cheaply made ones obtained from Saturday night
specials.
</P>
<P>
The University of California-Davis study released today is
based on 1995 police records.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Sacramento's crime rate was higher than almost every
city of comparable size or larger in California, and worse than
metropolises such as Dallas, Houston or New York City.
</P>
<P>
Most confiscated guns had no ownership records, and two of
every five that did had been stolen, researchers found. And nearly
half of those arrested with illegally guns were aged between 12
and 24.
</P>
<P>
The study was the first of its kind since it was based on
police statistics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southeast European Parliament Summit Ends in Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The two-day meeting of the
southeast European parliament summit ended here today with the
final resolution allowing the setting up of a parliamentary
advisory assembly to strengthen cooperation between the
legislatures in the region.
</P>
<P>
According to the final resolution, the presidents of
parliaments will at their next meeting decide on the conditions
and framework for establishing the assembly and assign the
realization of the plan to a working group.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also underlines the European orientation of the
states of the region and contains a decision to formally establish
dialogue between the national assemblies by organizing meetings of
the presidents of the region's parliaments on a regular and
rotating basis.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the final session today, Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis underscored the importance of the parliaments of the
region in "escaping from the past" and in promoting and
consolidating democracy in the countries of southeastern Europe,
considering a necessity dialogue in the framework of the
parliaments for the forging of new policies, contacts among them,
and the expansion of their relations with the Europarliament in
order to make clear Europe's responsibility for its region.
</P>
<P>
The first-ever meeting of its kind was attended by the
presidents of parliament of Greece, Albania, Bulgaria, Romania,
Yugoslavia and the former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia, with
observers from the parliamentary assemblies of international
organizations such as the Council of Europe, the Black Sea
Economic Cooperation and the Western European Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
