<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Plunge on Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial
average slid more than 100 points today among mounting fears that
profit growth would be too strong and ignite spending.
</P>
<P>
The Dow fell 119.10, or nearly 1.5 percent, to 7,938.88, after
recovering from a 161-point plunge.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 12-to-7 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 595.98 million
shares as against 504.68 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock measures also turned sharply lower despite a
strong bond market, where interest rates fell.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 10.47 to 955.25 after
recovering partially from a 15-point drop, and the NYSE composite
index fell 4.59 to 502.30.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index, down as much as 31 points during
the session, fell 23.71 to 1,699.66.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 fell 5.58 to 457.16 for its third consecutive
losing session, and the small-company dominated American Stock
Exchange composite index fell 5.96 to 708.38.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department reported that consumer prices rose just 0.2
percent last month, less than expectation of the market.
</P>
<P>
For the most part, today's third-quarter reports by bellwethers
such as Coca-Cola, Sears and Compaq Computer seemed to reinforce
the trend toward generally strong results for the July-September
period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
