<HEADLINE> US "Disappointed" at Mandela's Plan to Visit Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States expressed
"disappointment" today at South African President Nelson Mandela
for his plan to visit Libya on his way to attend a Commonwealth
summit.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that diplomatic contacts (with Libya) ought to be
maintained at a low level, and we would be disappointed with a
visit of any head of state," State Department spokesman James
Foley said at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
The South African embassy in Rabat, Morocco, announced Tuesday
that President Mandela will go to Libya and Egypt on his way to
the Commonwealth summit to be held in Edinburgh, Scotland, on
October 24-27 and visit Morocco on October 27 on his way back
home.
</P>
<P>
The statement said Mandela's visit to Libya was in response to
a long-standing invitation from Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi.
</P>
<P>
"Libya is a country which was very supportive of the South
African liberation movements during the struggle against apartheid
and is one of the countries that the president has not visited
since his inauguration," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
But the United States regarded the visit as a "violation" of
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"We would reiterate the fact that, according to U.N. Security
Council Resolutions 748 and 883, flights into Tripoli are a
violation of sanctions. So I think that would be a very specific
concern," Foley said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
