<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US FMC to Bar Japanese Ships from US Ports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The Federal Maritime
Commission (FMC) is ready today to order the bar of Japanese cargo
ships from entering U.S. ports, but delayed enforcement for a day
hoping that last-minute talks could resolve the trade disputes.
</P>
<P>
The FMC, an independent government agency, ordered the action
after the Japanese shipping companies have expressed their firm
stand that they do not plan to pay an estimated 4 million U.S.
dollars in fines levied by the United States.
</P>
<P>
A Japanese official said earlier this week in Tokyo that the
United States would find itself in the "shameful" position of
taking money from innocent parties if Japanese shippers were
forced to pay penalty surcharged in a bilateral ports disputes.
</P>
<P>
The fines were imposed after negotiators between the two
countries failed to find a solution on American demands for freer
access to Japanese ports. The U.S. side has set October 15 as the
deadline for the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said the United States and
Japan were in negotiations over the matter and that the White
House had sought a delay in the commission's actions while the
talks were going on.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions, which amount to 100,000 dollars per vessel, were
levied on Japanese cargo ships entering U.S. ports beginning
September 4. However, the three major Japanese shipping companies
involved had until Wednesday to actually pay the fines.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions, the first imposed on Japan in a decade, came
during a shipping dispute that has simmered for years.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and other foreign shipping lines complained that Japan
requires all shippers to receive prior approval for even the most
minor operational changes in handling cargo at Japanese ports.
Negotiations to loosen the restrictions have failed to produce
changes acceptable to the U.S. side. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greenpeace Urges Ban on Genetically Altered Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Greenpeace urged European
environment ministers meeting in Luxembourg today to protect the
right of European nations to refuse genetically engineered crops.
</P>
<P>
The European Council of Ministers will discuss the
controversial genetically engineered Novartis maize, which Austria
and Luxembourg have tried to ban on health and environmental
grounds. Under pressure from the United States, the European
Commission is trying to overrule their national import bans.
</P>
<P>
At today's meeting in Luxembourg, Greenpeace activists
displayed a cartoon showing the Statue of Liberty with European
Commission President Jacques Santer's face.
</P>
<P>
At the same time in Paris, activists hung a banner at the
French Statue of Liberty on the Seine, with the words "Protect
Europe's right to ban genetech maize." A chef's hat was also put
on the statue.
</P>
<P>
"US trade interests are forcing Novartis' genetically
engineered (GE) maize into Europe," said Susan Leubuscher of
Greenpeace's European Unit, "and the European Commission is
abusing its power by sacrificing European countries' democratic
rights, endangering the environment and putting at risk consumers
health protection."
</P>
<P>
Leubuscher asked the member states of the European Union to
insist that the Commission withdraw its proposal to deny Austria
and Luxembourg their right to ban the import of the GE maize.
</P>
<P>
Greenpeace is also calling on France as the country which
originally authorized the maize to withdraw that authorization.
Even France itself has refused to add the GE maize on its national
plant variety list, thereby preventing the large-scale growing of
this GE maize by its farmers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
