<HEADLINE> US Dollar Falls Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar slid sharply
against the Japanese yen in more than five weeks on fears of a
trade war after the United States moved today to ban Japanese
ships from using its ports.
</P>
<P>
Also weighing down the dollar was speculation that the Japanese
government may soon unveil a new plan to boost the nation's
sluggish economy.
</P>
<P>
The dollar closed at 119.65 yen, down from 121.16 Wednesday.
The drop of more than 1.5 yen was the biggest daily decline for
the dollar since September 9, when it fell more than 2.3 yen.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also fell to 1.7435 German marks from late
Wednesday's 1.7475. But the dollar rose against the British pound,
which slipped to 1.6179 U.S. dollars from 1.6239 U.S. dollars
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Also pressuring the dollar today was a U.S. government report
of consumer prices showing tame inflation. That reduced hopes that
the Federal Reserve would soon raise interest rates to slow the
economy.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday: 1.4550 Swiss francs, down from 1.4585; 5.8503 French
francs, down from 5.8575; 1,703 Italian lire, down from 1,707; and
1.3860 Canadian dollars, unchanged from Wednesday. 
</P>
