<HEADLINE> Kenyan Investors Urged to Be More Competitive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Finance Minister
Musalia Mudavadi today called on Kenyan investors to take
appropriate steps to enhance their competitive edge against
foreign investors for survival and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of Kenya Breweries Ltd. (KBL) new
bottling line here today, he noted that with the gradual
liberalization of Kenya's economy, the level of protection had
now reduced substantially in the country.
</P>
<P>
The minister urged all industries in Kenya to improve their
efficiency and quality of their goods and services if they want
to survive and prosper in the liberalized economy.
</P>
<P>
In order to create a market friendly environment, Mudavadi
said, his government has implemented prudent macro-economic
policies, reduced government borrowing, improved efficiency in
the financial markets and the condition of basic infrastructure
facilities.
</P>
<P>
The minister disclosed that the Kenyan government was
committed to the expansion of the overall investment from the
present level of 20 percent of GDP to at least 23 percent in
order to generate and sustain higher economic growth rates.
</P>
<P>
Mudavadi paid a high tribute to KBL as it has made efforts to
improve its efficiency and product quality by installing a modern
production line and achieving the international quality standard
ISO 9002.
</P>
<P>
The new bottling line which is said to be the fastest and most
modern bottling line on the African continent has a bottling
capacity of 80,000 bottles per hour.
</P>
<P>
The KBL is the second biggest brewing group in Africa with a
total brewing capacity of more than 4.5 million litres of beer
every year at its three breweries in Kenya. 
</P>
