<HEADLINE> Kohl Denies Rumors About Early Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 16 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
today made clear that if being re-elected in next year's general
elections, he would stay in office until 2002, denying rumors that
he is considering an early handover.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Germany ZDF television network, Kohl
said his candidacy for office in the 1998 elections was for the
full four-year term. "No chancellor would stand for part of it.
That would be the very last thing that I would do," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kohl unleashed speculations about an early handover by a
surprise announcement on Wednesday that he wanted his key aide
Wolfgang Schaeuble to succeed him in the future.
</P>
<P>
"I would like Wolfgang Schaeuble to be chancellor some day," he
said at the end of a three-day congress of his Christian
Democratic Union (CDU) party in the eastern German city of
Leipzig.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, 67, has been German chancellor for uninterrupted 15
years. He already ranks as Europe's longest-serving political
leader and the most durable German chancellor of this century.
</P>
<P>
By announcing his intention to seek another term of office in
April this year, Kohl said he felt obliged to guide Germany into
the new century in a united Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
