<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's First Lady Appeals to Improve Lives of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Society should be more involved
in improving the lives of street children as it is their right to
be protected, Zimbabwe's first lady Grace Mugabe said here today.
</P>
<P>
Opening a one-day workshop on rehabilitating street children,
Mrs. Mugabe said, "I believe that convincing society to view the
plight of street children as their own problem is an uphill
battle," adding that the struggle should not be given up.
</P>
<P>
The first lady said there was a need to observe the rights of
children in conformity with international conventions such as
United Nations Universal Declaration of Human Rights and the U.N.
Convention on the Rights of the Child.
</P>
<P>
"We, therefore, have the obligation to ensure that our
children's rights to survive and develop to their fullest
potential are upheld," she said.
</P>
<P>
Harare Mayor Solomon Tawengwa said at the workshop that
children were living in the streets through no fault of theirs,
and called on society to respect these children as human beings.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics indicate that Harare alone has more than
1,000 street children, half of whom live in the central business
district. About 3,000 children live in and sleep on the streets
countrywide and another 12,000 to 15,000 come daily to the
streets to look for sustenance in this country which has about
one million orphans.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, which was attended by top government officials,
representatives from urban local authorities and the private
sector, discussed the abuse of street children and the measures
that could be taken to stop it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
