<HEADLINE> Conditions in Some UK Jails Dreadful, Says Chief Inspector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Chief Inspector of
Prisons David Ramsbotham has launched an outspoken attack on
jails, warning that conditions in some jails are as bad as a
century ago.
</P>
<P>
Ramsbotham, Britain's most senior inspector of prisons, said
Wednesday that conditions in some jails were what he would expect
in jails in the last century and that standards were dropping
below the minimum promised by the Prison Service.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Home Secretary Jack Straw to carry out an urgent
examination of the entire system, which he said are collapsing
because of pressure from overcrowding and lack of funding.
</P>
<P>
His comment followed a report published Wednesday on his visit
in March to Lincoln adult prison which he said was in a "dreadful
state", with ripped and stained mattresses, and encrusted food on
the walls and ceilings.
</P>
<P>
He said that prison managers "must feel extremely concerned
about the future, in many other prisons, as numbers continue to
rise".
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the prison population in England and wales
has kept on rising, which stands now at a record 63,000. 
</P>
