<HEADLINE> Bank Account Opened in Angola to Collect Fund for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- A bank account named "Fao
Telealimento" was opened today at Angola's commercial and
industrial banks in Luanda to collect fund for farmers to brace
them up for natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
The act is a measure taken to answer the call by the United
Nations Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) made at the
summit on food held in Rome in 1996.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony to mark the opening of the bank account, the
Ministry of Fisheries put in 5,000 US dollars, whereas the
Angolan Commercial and Industrial Bank made a deposit of 300
million Readjusted Kwanza (about 1,111 US dollars) in the
account.
</P>
<P>
Pierre Gence, FAO representative in Angola, urged to give much
publicity to the account while calling for the utmost
transparency to the management and application of the money in
the account.
</P>
<P>
All money in the bank account will be used in agricultural
projects to ensure food security for the Angolan people, he said,
adding that FAO will not use a single cent in the account for its
own administrative expenses.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the bank account is part of the activities to
mark today's World Food Day. 
</P>
