<HEADLINE> Britain to Order Seven New Trident Missiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The British government has
announced that Britain would spend almost 100 million pounds
(about 160 million U.S. dollars) on seven new missiles for its
Trident nuclear submarines in an effort to reinforce its nuclear
deterrent force.
</P>
<P>
John Gilbert, Britain's minister for defense procurement, said
in a written statement to the House of Lords: "This will bring the
number of Trident missiles purchased or ordered by the UK to 58."
</P>
<P>
Explaining the new arms purchase, Gilbert said: "For the
present, however, we are committed to the maintenance of a minimum
level of deterrence, and this missile order is consistent with
that aim."
</P>
<P>
"Our future missile and warhead requirements remain under
consideration in the forthcoming strategic defense review," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, British Defense Secretary George Robertson flatly
denied the new missile order was an expansion of the country's
Trident nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
"This is not something that is new or different, it was known
about, and they are of course budgeted for," Robertson said in a
HBC Radio interview.
</P>
<P>
Robertson stressed that the new missiles were the last part of
the Trident program and the parts ordered were missile bodies and
not nuclear warheads. 
</P>
