<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- British business leaders have
called on the British government to clarify its position on the
European Monetary Union (EMU) following a spate of reports
suggesting Britain was poised to join the single currency shortly
after its launch.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Labor government remained undecided over its
first-wave membership of the single currency due to be launched on
January 1 1999, provoking various speculations over London's EMU
stance.
</P>
<P>
Adair Turner, the director-general of the Confederation of
British Industry, is quoted by the Times newspaper as saying that
the current muddle showed that the Government needed to have
clearer position.
</P>
<P>
Turner noted that he doubted whether any existing international
investors would close their factories in Britain simply because
London refused to sign up.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed if it became obvious that Britain was not
joining the single European currency named euro in the long term,
it could put off future investment.
</P>
<P>
"The issue is not about existing investment, it is whether over
time incremental new investment into existing facilities or new
facilities would be somewhat higher or lower if we were out of
EMU," he said.
</P>
<P>
The pro-EMU European Movement said that statements from a
number of major companies showed that thousands of jobs would be
at risk if Britain stayed out.
</P>
<P>
"Any government will have to think carefully about the costs of
exclusion (from the single currency)," it said in a statement.
</P>
