<HEADLINE> GM Works Council Fears Huge Job Losses in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 16 (Xinhua) -- General Motors' European works
council today said that the U.S. carmaker could eliminate up to 14
percent of its employment in Europe if an efficiency study of
company was carried out.
</P>
<P>
The works council said after a meeting in Ruesselsheim, Germany
that it feared that about 12,000 jobs might be cut in the coming
years at GM's factories in Germany, Britain, Belgium, Spain,
Portugal and Austria. In Germany alone, job losses could total
6,000 to 8,000.
</P>
<P>
At the GM plant in Antwerp of Belgium, the management already
announced today that 1,900 of the 7,800 jobs there would be cut
over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
Calling on the management of the GM European operations to stop
the so-called Template study, the council's chairman, Rudolf
Mueller, said the study was aimed exclusively at cutting jobs and
did not take into account the higher quality advantage of the GM
factories in Europe. 
</P>
