<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Official Optimistic of Eliminating Extreme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) Administrator James Gustave Speth has said that
"extreme poverty can be eliminated in a generation, with enough
will, wisdom and work."
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in a message to mark October 17,
International Day for Eradication of Poverty, which was
designated by the U.N. General Assembly to focus global attention
on the scourge of poverty and social deprivation.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated by UNDP that 1.3 billion people live in
extreme poverty and lack basic health, sanitation and education
services, surviving on less than one US dollar a day.
</P>
<P>
"The world has already made great strides in relieving the
worst aspects of poverty," Speth said, adding that much progress
has been achieved in this regard in the last five decades than in
the last five centuries.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that "Women and children are still
disproportionately affected by poverty. Not only do they earn
less incomes than men, but their opportunities to increase
earnings are more limited because of their reproductive and
household responsibilities, and because they have little access
to land, credit, and jobs that can help them and their children
overcome poverty."
</P>
<P>
"Many of the least developed countries in sub-Saharan Africa
and south Asia have gained much less than other developing
countries as a whole. Violent conflicts, the spread of HIV and
AIDS and environmental degradation have pushed millions back into
poverty in the past 15 years," Speth pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"We have no ethical alternative but to take on this challenge
with all the seriousness it deserves," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Poverty is not inevitable," he said, stressing that the rise
in poverty in recent years can be reversed if all governments
take more seriously the commitments they have already made to
reduce poverty at home and in the rest of the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
