<HEADLINE> Mandela Orders New Security Strategy in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 16 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela today ordered police and defense chiefs to refine
measures already in place to combat crime and violence on the
Cape Flats in Western Cape, South African Press Association
reported.
</P>
<P>
Mandela called a special security meeting today after talks
with concerned community representatives Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Residents of the violence-plagued Cape Flats can expect an
increase in visible policing and the carrying out of special
security operations, Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi
told reporters after the meeting in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
He said a follow-up meeting will be held Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting chaired by Defense Minister Joe Modise,
included Mufamadi, Police Commissioner George Fivaz, and National
Defense Force chief George Meiring.
</P>
<P>
Justice Minister Dullah Omar, Finance Minister Trevor Manuel
and deputy intelligence minister, Joe Nhlanhla, were also present
for part of the talks.
</P>
<P>
Mandela attended part of the meeting before leaving for
another engagement.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held in response to an open letter from the
Western Cape Anti-crime Forum, which said people in the province
were at war.
</P>
<P>
The forum said its members had lost confidence in Mufamadi,
his provincial counterpart and premier of the province, Hernus
Kriel, to protect innocent residents of Cape Flats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
