<HEADLINE> U.S. Believes Peace Process in Angola Will Be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Paul Hare, special envoy for
U.S. President Bill Clinton said here today that his government
believes Angolan Peace Process will be a success despite the
great difficulty it confronts.
</P>
<P>
Hare, who is currently in Angola for a four-day visit, made
the statement while summarizing his visit at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the U.S. government was sure that problems
facing the peace process will be settled with satisfactory
results.
</P>
<P>
The major problems confronting the peace process are
"psychological", mainly due to the lack of mutual trust between
the warring sides, namely the Angolan government and former rebel
movement the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA).
</P>
<P>
He cited the re-establishment of national authority in
UNITA-occupied areas and the total demobilization of UNITA forces
as two biggest problems during the implementation of the Lusaka
Peace Accord.
</P>
<P>
Hare also expressed his worries over the fact that UNITA has
not turned the radio it controlled into a commercial one.
</P>
<P>
Hare admitted that the peace process has made major progress
concerning some key issues. He urged both sides to be committed
to their obligations contained in Lusaka Peace Accord to truly
put an end to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The special envoy arrived here on October 13 to get to know
the latest developments in Angolan Peace Process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
