<HEADLINE> NATO HQ Celebrates 30 Years in Brussels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization put up a photo exhibition to commemorate NATO
headquarters' 30 years in Brussels today.
</P>
<P>
On October 16 of 1967, the international staff and the then 15
national delegations to the North Atlantic Council, executive body
of NATO, moved to their new headquarters in the Belgian capital.
</P>
<P>
The decision to move away from France was taken by the council
in its Paris meeting in December 1966 and construction of the new
headquarters over the former runways of the old Brussels airport
started in March 1967 and completed in 29 weeks.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made after France decided to withdraw from
NATO's military structure.
</P>
<P>
The issue of Belgium becoming the host nation to NATO had been
at the forefront of parliamentary debates in Belgium. The debates
concluded with a motion of support.
</P>
<P>
Belgian Foreign Minister Erik Derycke said: "Over the course of
the last 30 years which have seen the concentration of many
international organizations in Brussels, the Belgian authorities
have taken great pride in acting as the host nation to the
Atlantic alliance.
</P>
<P>
"This pride is shared by a great number of Belgian citizens
who, in one way or another, have been associated with the task of
welcoming the thousands of people who have come to live in Belgium
as NATO staff, civilian or military." 
</P>
</TEXT>
