<HEADLINE> Uganda Sets Local Election Dates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The Uganda electoral
commission has set dates for the local governments elections,
reported radio Uganda today.
</P>
<P>
Elections of village executive committees will be held on
different dates, the report quoted the commission's announcement
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The announcement issued today said the elections of village
executive committees will held on first of November this year.
</P>
<P>
It said elections of parish executive committees will be held
on November 8 while elections of youth and woman committees at
village and parish levels will be held on November 4, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Details of regarding elections at county or municipality,
sub-county or town, or division and district levels will be
announced soon, the announcement added.
</P>
<P>
According to the national resistance movement system in
Uganda, the country has five levels of local governments under
the central government, that is from district councils down to
county councils, sub-county councils, parish councils and village
councils.
</P>
<P>
Uganda held its first direct election of president in May 1996
while parliamentary elections were held in June the same year.
</P>
<P>
In November 1996, the Ugandan central government announced
that local government elections are to be held between March and
April 1997, but were postponed several times due to the lack of
election fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
