<HEADLINE> Qin: Resources Availability Essential to Promote Social </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 16 (Xinhua) -- To strengthen
international cooperation and make resources available were
essential to promote the social development, Qin Huasun, Chinese
Permanent Representative to the United Nations, stressed here
today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the fifty-second session of the General Assembly on
the implementation of the outcome of the World Summit for Social
Development, Qin Huasun said since the 1995 Copenhagen World
Summit for Social Development, the question of social development
had drawn increasing attention from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
Qin said the short, mid and long-term strategies and plans for
social development formulated by many countries and concrete
measures taken in this regard have brought about positive
progress in the implementation of the outcome of the summit at
the national level.
</P>
<P>
Qin said the resolutions adopted by the General Assembly,
Economic and Social Council and the Commission on Social
Development for the implementation of the outcome had also played
a positive role in promoting social development.
</P>
<P>
Qin pointed out action had been rather slow in developing
substantive international cooperation promised at the summit and
concern on this question was therefore not ill founded.
</P>
<P>
Qin said poverty was the major obstacle to social development
as well as a serious threat to peace and stability. To eradicate
poverty was an imperious mission of the international
community. It was made the first of the three core issues at the
summit. But no major improvement has been made in the social
situation of the world more than two years after the Summit.
</P>
<P>
Qin stressed developed countries should fulfill their
obligations to contribute at an early date 0.7% of the GNP to
official development aid and take more concrete measures for
developing countries in economic assistance, technological
cooperation and debt reduction and remission.
</P>
<P>
He added the United States should focus its efforts for
social development on developing countries and play a central
coordinating role in promoting the follow-up to the Summit.
</P>
</TEXT>
