<HEADLINE> Canadian Carriers Vie for Asian Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The two major carriers in Canada
are vying for the lucrative routes to Asia.
</P>
<P>
Air Canada is reported to be lobbying the government for
permission to fly more often to Hong Kong and other Asian
destinations.
</P>
<P>
Its rival Canadian Airlines International has said it will
oppose any federal government move to increase Air Canada's access
to Asia.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the matter, Canadian president and Chief executive
Kevin Benson said the Calgary-based carrier is opposed to any
out-of-hand changes.
</P>
<P>
The current policy under which the government allocates routes
is working well enough, he was quoted as saying by reports today.
</P>
<P>
Air Canada thinks otherwise. It has been pushing for reforms to
the policy so as to obtain permission to increase its flights to
Asia.
</P>
<P>
And its president and chief executive Lamar Durret has met with
Transport Minister David Collenette to make that pitch.
</P>
<P>
The Montreal-based carrier says Canada's airlines are losing
business to Asian competitors.
</P>
<P>
To increase its competitiveness, the carrier said it is
acquiring planes in 2002 that can fly non-stop from Toronto to
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Canadian Airlines has made Vancouver its
operating hub so it can capitalize on the Asian market.
</P>
<P>
So far, the Canadian government has made no commitments on new
routes other than to say that it is monitoring things. 
</P>
</TEXT>
