<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Continues Bombarding S. Leone Junta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The west African peacekeeping force
(ECOMOG) today continued air attacks at the military junta in
Freetown, capital of Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, angry youths turned out to burn down houses and property
belonging to supporters of the ousted government, according to the
British Broadcasting Corporation.
</P>
<P>
At around 2:30 this afternoon, ECOMOG jets flew over Freetown again
and dropped bombs at a junta-owned FM radio station.
</P>
<P>
"Since then there is complete silence," the report said.
</P>
<P>
In another area of the city, ECOMOG bombardment also destroyed a
house belonging to a well-known businessman despite the anti-aircraft
guns in the house's compound aiming at the jets.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG jets attacked telecommunications installations Wednesday,
disrupting communications in the city.
</P>
<P>
To retaliate Wednesday's ECOMOG air raid, youths who back the junta
went out this morning attacking houses belonging to supporters of
ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Last week, junta's spokesman Aliu Kamara said if there were any
more bombing and attacks, the supporters of the ousted government will
be targeted.
</P>
<P>
The actions have brought fears into the houses of those who call
themselves as supporters of Kabbah, or indeed the supporters of
democracy, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, another new dimension is that the junta is
taking up soldiers who are displaying their reluctance to fight.
</P>
<P>
Military trucks have been touring around the city today arresting
soldiers who have gone AWOL.
</P>
<P>
There seems to quite a large number of soldiers who are refusing to
be used as cannon fodder to get into fight with ECOMOG whose troops
are much better equipped.
</P>
<P>
This has led to the latest speculation in Freetown that the junta
is doing all it can to get as many as soldiers together to mount a new
attack on the ECOMOG bases at Lungi and Jui outside the capital
tonight, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The fresh exchanges of fire followed a United Nations Security
Council sanctions on Sierra Leone announced last Wednesday aimed at
reinstating the legitimate government led by President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah which was ousted in the coup last May.
</P>
<P>
The UN decision is seen as a strong support to west African
countries' economic sanctions and embargo on Sierra Leone, which is
being enforced by ECOMOG.  
</P>
</TEXT>
