<HEADLINE> E. Africa to Better Cooperate in Wildlife </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Leading tourism officials from
Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda today reached a memorandum of mutual
understanding to promote their cooperation on wildlife protection
and eco-tourism.
</P>
<P>
The three eastern African countries should market the region
as one destination for tourists and cooperate with each other
more on personnel training and wildlife security, they agreed at
the end of the East African Wildlife Cooperation meeting.
</P>
<P>
They also suggested the joint construction of a tourism
communication network and a surveillance unit, especially on
rhino monitoring.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to establish a common mechanism to coordinate
their efforts to improve the management of the cross-border
ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
The benefits expected from the collaboration among the three
countries also include smooth cross-border movement of tourists
and security of animals during inter-country migrations.
</P>
<P>
"East Africa has a unique concentration of wildlife species
not found anywhere else in the world, if properly utilized, can
make the region highly developed," said Executive Secretary of
the East Africa Cooperation (EAC) Francis Muthaurwa at the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
"Wildlife have no borders," he said, urging the three EAC
member states to cooperate more in the areas such as health
management of animals, infrastructural development and animals
security.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-one delegates, including Executive Director of Uganda
Wildlife Authority Yakobo Moyini, Chief Preventive Officer in
Tanzanian Tourism Ministry Musa Lyimo, and Director of Kenya
Wildlife Service David Western, attended the two-day workshop.
</P>
</TEXT>
