<HEADLINE> UK Tory Warns of Future Trade Conflict with US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 16 (Xinhua) - Tory legal affairs spokesman
Euro-MP Bryan Cassidy urged: Europe and the USA must continue
talks if Europe wants to prevent conflict.
</P>
<P>
Cassidy, also Vice-President of Parliament's US delegation and
a strident critic of the provocative Helms-Burton, made the
remarks when he returns from the USA today.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving, he commented: "EU-US relations are crucial to
global economic and political stability. US politicians are
playing with fire when they support laws like Helms-Burton that
punish foreign citizens and companies for normal overseas
trading."
</P>
<P>
Attacking the stubborn attitude of the US Congress, Cassidy
waarned: " The EU must not be lulled into a false sense of
progress as talks go on. The US mood is toughening as States like
Massachusetts complicate the issue with further extra-territorial
laws."
</P>
<P>
"The signal from Brussels must be clear: talks can continue but
only until the end of December. When EU foreign ministers meet
next week, they must send a strong signal," he added.
</P>
<P>
With a study by the European-American Business Council entitled
"Is The Price Too High? The Cost Of US Sanction Policy"
highlighting fears of many US businessmen, Cassidy pointed out:
"The irony is that this excessive US pressure is not only
distorting international trade, but hurting US firms."
</P>
<P>
"American companies complain that EU firms are now reluctant
either to enter into joint ventures, or to invest in US business,
for fear of sanction," he added.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Euro-MPs will meet in Strasbourge next
week to debate main EU policy priorities for 1998. Given the lack
of agreement over Helms-Burton, Cassidy noted: "EU Commissioners
can expect tough questions if tackling this crisis is not a top
priority." 
</P>
