<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: U.S. to Spend More on Military Electronics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. military is
spending more on electronics procurement through 2007, from the
current 18.5 billion U.S. dollars to 23.8 billion dollars,
although the overall defense spending is expected to continue
declining, the Defense News said in its latest edition.
</P>
<P>
Citing the 10-Year Defense and NASA Electronics Forecast
released last week, the weekly said overall spending on military
electronic components is expected to rise from 51.5 billion
dollars to 58.9 billion dollars in 2007.
</P>
<P>
A large chunk of the increased spending during the next decade
can be traced to the Pentagon's quest to win information
superiority. "The military wants U.S. forces to be virtually
unchallenged in collecting and distributing information while
denying an enemy the same capabilities," the Defense News said.
</P>
<P>
Joint service and international aircraft programs will
flourish, Cecil Black, Boeing's manager of business analysis for
government affairs, said.
</P>
<P>
Factors driving up the procurement of aircraft electronic
systems include the growing reliance on precision-strike
capabilities, surveillance and intelligence gathering, and command
and control for existing and planned aircraft, he said.
</P>
<P>
Electronics procurement for military aircraft, including
unmanned aerial vehicles, will grow from 5.7 billion dollars in
1998 to 7.7 billion dollars, or 44 percent of the aircraft
procurement budget of 17.5 billion dollars predicted in 2007, the
forecast said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
