<HEADLINE> U.S. Army to Spend One-Third on Digitization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Army will devote
about one-third of its research, development and acquisition
budget, or 28 billion U.S. dollars, to digitization in the next
five years to place the service on the path to a future digitized
battlefield, the Defense News said in its latest edition.
</P>
<P>
Digitization is a method of using information technologies to
process massive amounts of information nearly simultaneously and
is expected to give the Army a decisive battlefield advantage in
the information age.
</P>
<P>
It includes tactical radios, sensors, satellite communication,
computers, navigation systems, and missile and munition guidance
systems, among many other things.
</P>
<P>
The service has been experimenting in a series of field
maneuvers, simulation exercises and reformed acquisition processes
to see what effect advanced information technologies have on the
battlefield, the weekly said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
