<HEADLINE> Four French Tourists Freed by Yemeni Tribesmen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Yemeni security forces today
succeeded in obtaining the release by tribesman of four French
tourists kidnapped on Wednesday, according to the Yemeni News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
The news agency quoted a source from the Interior Ministry as
saying that the tourists, three women and a man, have returned
safely to the town of Saada, 270 kilometers north of the capital
Sanaa.
</P>
<P>
The French tourists were abducted on their way to Saada by
eight tribesman, who demanded a ransom of money and vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Without detailing how this incident was settled, the Interior
Ministry source only said the criminals will be duly punished.
</P>
<P>
He said the acts of sabotage have harmed the nation and its
reputation. Kidnapping has become a common ploy used by tribes to
demand for money and financing.
</P>
<P>
A total of 26 foreigners had been abducted in the country, one
of the poorest in the Arab world, but they were later freed
unharmed.
</P>
<P>
The Interior Ministry has vowed to step up security for foreign
tourists and crack down hard on those "who jeopardize the
security, stability and tranquility of the whole society." 
</P>
