<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Development Financing Bears on Developing Countries' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 16 (Xinhua) -- At a time when economic
globalization was accelerating, financing of development was an
issue of prime importance, Yu Qingtai, Chinese delegate to the
Second Committee, said here today.
</P>
<P>
Development financing directly bore on whether the developing
countries could seize opportunities and achieve economic
development in the years beyond the century so as to contribute to
regional and global economic development, Yu said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Second Committee at the 52nd session of the
General Assembly on financing of development and the debt problem,
Yu said that to many developing countries, the least developed in
particular, official development assistance remained an important
source of external funding, playing an irreplaceable role.
</P>
<P>
Yu said a source of concern was that official development
assistance had kept decreasing over the years, with last year's
rate dropping to 0.25 percent, a historic new low. The developed
countries should realize that by doing so, they could only serve
their narrow and short-term interests.
</P>
<P>
Yu said official development assistance was not charity, but
rather, it was a long-term investment for developed countries'
own interests. It was also an inescapable moral responsibility. He
called on the developed countries to demonstrate political will to
honor their commitments by reversing the downward trend.
</P>
<P>
He said external debt was a question closely related to the
financing of development. Owing to the joint efforts of the
international community and the debtor countries, the debt issue
had been eased somewhat throughout the world. But there was still
a long way to go before the ultimate objective of a thorough and
comprehensive resolution could be achieved.
</P>
<P>
He said debt burden, in fact, was still plaguing a considerable
number of developing countries. He hoped that the international
community, and particularly financial institutions and creditor
countries, would take a more positive approach by taking into
account the special circumstance of the relevant developing
countries in eligibility criteria and application time-frame, so
as to contribute to the full implementation of the initiative at
an early date. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
