<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaian Foreign Investment Act Passed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, October 16 (Xinhua) - A Bulgarian Foreign Investment Act
was passed on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The law sets the procedure and terms of carrying out priority
investment projects in Bulgaria by Bulgarian and foreign
investors. The Council of Ministers must publish a list of regions
where investment projects are to be implemented within a month of
the Act's entry into force. The list will be updated on an annual
basis.
</P>
<P>
Priority investment projects must meet the following criteria:
over 5,000,000 US dollars in investment, over 100 jobs created and
investing in areas with unemployment above the country average
listed by the Cabinet. The companies implementing the projects
will have their profits tax cut by 50 per cent for ten years.
</P>
<P>
At the investor's request the Foreign Investment Agency
proposes to the competent authorities to grant limited real rights
on privately or municipally owned real property for the priority
investment project's implementation.
</P>
<P>
The law regulates the purchase of foreign exchange and its
transfer abroad by foreign nationals. This can be done after
presenting a receipt of taxes paid in the following cases:
realized return on investment, compensation for an investment
entity expropriated for state use, liquidation quota on
terminating the investment, amount received on selling the
investment entity, amount received after a compulsory winding-up.
</P>
<P>
A bank which transfers foreign exchange without the required
documents is liable to a penalty equal to the amount transferred.
Repeat offenders must pay double the transferred amount.
</P>
<P>
The law designates as foreign investment shares in commercial
partnerships, titles to buildings and limited real rights to real
property, titles to and limited real rights to movable property in
the form of fixed assets, titles to enterprises or to
self-contained parts of enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment can also be in the form of securities,
including Treasury bills and government bonds maturing in at least
six months and issued by the state, municipalities or other
Bulgarian juristic persons; loans repayable in at least 12 months;
intellectual property; rights proceeding from concession contracts
and management contracts.
</P>
<P>
When an international agreement to which Bulgaria is a party
offers more favorable terms of business to foreign nationals,
these terms apply.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian nationals with dual citizenship who are permanently
resident abroad may choose between the status of Bulgarian or
foreign national.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry, the National Statistical Institute, the
Central Depositary and the National Bank of Bulgaria quarterly
provide data on the type and amount of foreign investment, to be
used by the Foreign Investment Agency's information system.
</P>
<P>
The law exempts from VAT, tariffs and charges imported machines
and technological equipment, including water, air, rail and road
vehicles, which are a non-cash contribution by a foreign partner
or shareholder of a commercial partnership. The contribution must
be no less than the leva equivalent of 100,000 dollars at the
dollar/lev exchange rate at the time of valuation. VAT, tariffs
and charges are not levied on passenger vehicles, light trucks and
passenger/cargo vehicles with a carrying capacity up to 1.5 tons
when they are instrumental in effecting business deals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Consumer Prices Up 0.2 Percent in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. consumer price
increased by a small 0.2 percent in September despite the sharp
gain in energy costs, the U.S. Labor Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
It was the third month that the U.S. consumer prices increased
at the same slow level.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that declines in vegetable and pork prices
and auto financing charges helped slow the overall increase in
consumer prices.
</P>
<P>
Energy costs jumped by 1.3 percent in September after a 1.7
percent gain in August. Gasoline price rose 1.8 percent following
a 5.4 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
But food prices rose a barely detectable 0.1 percent while
vegetable prices slipped 0.9 percent and pork dropped by 0.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
New cars edged 0.1 percent higher and used cars 0.1 percent
lower. But lower interest rates produced a 1.3 percent drop in
auto finance charges.
</P>
<P>
For the first nine months of the year, the Consumer Price Index
in the U.S. rose at an annual rate of 1.8 percent comparing with a
3.3 percent increase in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the volatile food and energy, prices rose a tame 0.2
percent last month. For the year so far, this so-called core
inflation rate is rising at a 2.2 percent annual rate compared
with a 2.6 percent advance for all of last year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Labor Department also reported earlier this week that
the wholesale prices increased by 0.5 percent last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
