<HEADLINE> Cohen Denies Friction With Albright on Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen today denied reports that he had differences with
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright over whether to keep U.S.
troops in Bosnia beyond June next year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a speech to business leaders on
U.S. military spending and reform, Cohen said, "There has been no
disagreement between Secretary Albright and myself."
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Cohen publicly repeated his position against
any further deployment of U.S. troops in Bosnia after its mandate
ends in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
Albright favored retaining U.S. peacekeepers in Bosnia within
some larger international force after the so-called Stabilization
Force (SFOR) pulls out of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that no decision had been made on any future
deployment, Cohen today told reporters, "Reports about our battle
are greatly exaggerated. We work very closely together."
</P>
<P>
"We basically agree about the ending of SFOR's mission. We
also agree that Congress must play a role in any decision beyond
June of 1998," he said.
</P>
<P>
"And so reports that you read about, I think, have been
spontaneously generated, but not by virtue of any friction
between the two of us," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the defense budget signed by President Bill
Clinton for fiscal 1998, Clinton is allowed to provide financial
support to further deployment of U.S. troops in Bosnia after June
1998 if he explains reasons for doing so to Congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
