<HEADLINE> Turkey to Go Ahead with Maneuvers in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Deputy Prime Minister
Ismet Sezgin said here today that Turkey's planned military
exercises in Cyprus next month will go ahead as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Turkey had no intention to change its plan, Sezgin said at a
press conference. He added that the U.S. calls for reducing
tensions on the island was "late."
</P>
<P>
Turkey plans to hold maneuvers in northern Cyprus on November
3-5 and in the Mediterranean and Aegean region on November 1-8.
</P>
<P>
Sezgin, also defense minister, told the press that he will go
to northern Cyprus, where the Turkish Cypriots declared a
breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" recognized only by
Ankara, to monitor the Turkish maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
The planned Turkish war games were apparently a response to the
three-day joint Greek and Greek Cypriots' military exercises,
code-named "Nikiforos (Victorious) '97," in the Greek
Cypriots-controlled area on October 10-13.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing, Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman Omer
Akbel termed the Greek and Greek Cypriot exercises in Cyprus as "a
provocative action."
</P>
<P>
Turkey sent its warplanes to fly over Cyprus in the past
several days and meet Greek jets in the air, but no clashes
happened.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Cyprus accused Turkey of violating their airspace,
but Ankara denied.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Cyprus has become worse since the Cypriot
government signed a deal with Russia to purchase anti-aircraft
missiles in January this year.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish military has vowed to destroy the missiles if
diplomatic efforts fail to block their deployment, which it said
is a threat to Turkish security.
</P>
<P>
U.S. special envoy for Cyprus Richard Holbrooke urged all
parties concerned in the Cyprus problem to avoid actions of
increasing tensions during his visit to Ankara early this week.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot south and Turkish
Cypriot north since 1974 when Turkey sent troops to occupy the
northern third of the island in reaction to a failed coup seeking
union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations and international community have failed to
achieve any tangible results in realizing reunification of the
eastern Mediterranean island state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
