<HEADLINE> US: Russia Expands Ties With West Despite NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Russia has defied
predictions by some critics of NATO enlargement by accelerating
internal reform and expanding cooperation with the West, a top
State Department official said today.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made in a speech by Deputy Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott for delivery to the World Affairs Council of Boston
and copies were made available to reporters by the State
Department.
</P>
<P>
"President Yeltsin has beefed up his government with innovators
committed to economic modernization and integration," said
Talbott.
</P>
<P>
Talbott said Russian President Boris Yeltsin also has made
dramatic progress in reconciling differences with Ukraine,
participated in a Denver summit of leaders of developed countries
and advanced Russia's effort to join the World Trade Organization
and other international bodies.
</P>
<P>
Critics of the expansion of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) have argued that the process would strengthen
anti-reform groups in Russia and end Moscow's cooperation with the
West.
</P>
<P>
However, Russia continues its cooperation with the West,
Talbott noted, citing the fact that 1,400 Russian troops are
participating in the NATO-led Stabilization Force in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The Russian troops are under the command of Gen. Anatoly
Glebovich Krivalapov who, during the Cold War, spent much of his
career pointing intercontinental ballistic missiles at American
cities, said Talbott.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, Talbott admitted NATO enlargement worries many
Russians. "Many Russians still have in mind a Cold War image of
NATO," he said, stressing that these include Russian reformers,
who warn that the process threatens to strengthen these forces.
</P>
<P>
But Talbott said he believes the "risk is both exaggerated and
manageable."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and President Bill Clinton have tried to keep their
disagreement on the subject "within the bounds of an over-arching
cooperative relationship between Russia and the United States,"
Talbott said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
