<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Telecoms Satellite Sent Aloft In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XICHANG, October 17 (Xinhua) -- China sent an ApStar-2R
telecommunications satellite belonging to Hong Kong's Asia-Pacific
Satellite Telecommunications into orbit on a Long-March 3b rocket
at 03:13 today.
</P>
<P>
The rocket was launched at the Xichang Satellite Launching
Center in southwestern Sichuan province. The satellite separated
after 1,473 seconds of flight.
</P>
<P>
The Xi'an Satellite Monitoring Center reports that the
satellite has entered its orbit with an apogee of 47,922 km,
perigee of 201 km, and dip of 24.4 degrees.
</P>
<P>
This is the third launch of a Long-March 3b, which is a recent
development of the China Carrier Rocket Technology Institute. It
has a 5,000-kg payload and is the most powerful rocket developed
by China so far.
</P>
<P>
The maiden launch of Long-March 3b failed on February 15, 1996,
because of the changes of inertial reference in the the control
system. The second, on August 20 of this year, was a success,
thanks to technological improvement made after the first launch.
</P>
<P>
The 3,700 kg. ApStar-2R satellite, which has 28 c-band
transponders and 15 Ku-band transponders, is manufactured by the
U.S.'s Space System (Loral). With a a life span of 15 years, it
will be positioned at 76.5 degrees east longitude and over the
equator.
</P>
<P>
The Long-March 3b will be used to carry three more
telecommunications satellites in the near future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Social Security Gives Lowest Raise in Decade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The 44 million Americans
getting Social Security checks will see the payment grow by just
2.1 percent next year, the lowest cost-of-living raise in a
decade.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Social Security Commissioner Kenneth S. Apfel said today
the cost of living adjustment, or COLA, means the average monthly
check for retirees will rise by 16 dollars to 765 dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The maximum monthly payment for 6.5 million low income
individuals receiving Supplemental Security Income, known as SSI,
also will rise by 2.1 percent to 494 dollars. For a couple, the
maximum payment goes to 741 from 726 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The monthly checks for retirees, the biggest benefit program in
the U.S. federal budget spending, are adjusted annually to keep
inflation from eroding their buying power. Since 1975, the
adjustment has been automatic. It is calculated based on changes
in the Consumer Price Index from the third quarter of one year to
the corresponding quarter of the next.
</P>
<P>
Because of low inflation in the country, the yearly benefit
boosts have been below 3 percent since 1994. Next year's gain in
U.S. Social Security payment is the smallest since a record low
1.3 percent raise in 1987.
</P>
<P>
For 144 million working Americans, the maximum annual earnings
subject to Social Security payroll taxes next year will also rise
to 68,400 dollars from 65,400 dollars, though the rate at which
the earnings are taxed remains at 6.2 percent. That means a
maximum Social Security tax of 4,241 dollars in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
