<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Tourism to Hold General Assembly in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The 12th General Assembly of the
World Tourism Organization (WTO) is to open on October 20 in
Istanbul, the largest city in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
A press release from the WTO press center said today that the
five-day conference will be attended by around 1,000 delegates
from 131 countries, including 98 ministers and vice-ministers.
</P>
<P>
The participants are expected to discuss effective means to
ensure orderly and sustainable development of the tourist industry
in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Other topics, including tourism and local economic
development, tourism and environment protection, tourism and
taxation, will be taken up during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Speaking upon his arrival today at Istanbul's Ataturk Airport,
Francesco Frangialli, Secretary General of the Madrid-based
organization, said that the Istanbul conference is expected to
give an impetus to the development of the world's tourist industry.
</P>
<P>
The world tourism earned around 3.6 trillion U.S. dollars in
1996 and the figure is expected to climb to 7.8 trillion dollars
in 2006, according to figures released by the WTO.
</P>
<P>
WTO has 129 member states and four associate members. Its 11th
General Assembly was held in Cairo, Egypt in October 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
