<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Beer Brewing Industry Forging Ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
( By Wang Jinyu )
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 16 (Xinhua) -- With a new bottling line
commissioning here today, the Kenyan beer brewing industry has
enough capacity to meet the growing needs well into the next
millennium.
</P>
<P>
The new line which is believed to be the most modern bottling
line on the African continent has a capacity of 80,000 bottles
per hour, bringing the brewing capacity of the Kenya Breweries
Ltd. (KBL) to three million litres of beer a year.
</P>
<P>
The modernization of production equipment is one of a series
of initiatives taken by the KBL, the second largest brewing group
on the continent, to face the growing competition on the local
beer market.
</P>
<P>
With the gradual liberalization of Kenya's economy, the level
of protection has now been reduced substantially and local
investors have to improve their efficiency and quality if they
want to survive and prosper.
</P>
<P>
The KBL which has three breweries in the country has recently
earned the accolade of being the first brewery in Africa to
achieve the international quality standard ISO 9002 at the
Nairobi and Kisumu breweries.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,300 employees from both management and workers of
the company were trained in exacting quality improvement programs
during the past two years.
</P>
<P>
The KBL will also carry out a re-assessment of key operational
issues which in the long run will lead to substantial cost
savings and efficiencies.
</P>
<P>
The company intends to build a more versatile workforce
through training and manpower development for all staff in a bid
to enhance competitive edge against foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, substantial business opportunities continue
to emerge in East Africa with the advent of renewed cooperation
between the governments and people of Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
To cope with the growing demands for its products, the company
has already invested 1.5 billion Kenyan Shillings (about 25
million U.S. Dollars) in installing one bottling line in Kenya
and the other in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The KBL Chairman Jeremiah Kiereini today announced that his
company had made a plan to raise a further 1.5 billion shillings
of new capital to be used to set up a brewery in Tanzania which
is expected to start brewing by December 1998.
</P>
<P>
The company remains committed towards self sufficiency in the
supply of raw materials and provides financial and technical help
to local barley farmers in order to guarantee a continued supply
of quality malt.
</P>
<P>
In cooperation with local and international institutions, the
company has carried out continuous researches aimed at releasing
a new variety of barley, the KHBI 308-5, to replace the Bima
variety by November this year.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's beer brewing industry dates back to 1922 and as early
as in 1934 the KBL won its first Gold Medal in the Mode
Selection.
</P>
<P>
This year, at the International Monde Selection Awards held in
Brussels, the KBL won six Gold and two Silver medals for its
beers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
