<HEADLINE> PUK Not Target of Turkish Operations: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkey said today that the
Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) had never been a target of its
military operations in northern Iraq, the Anatolia News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
"The Turkish government troops have not staged an operation
against the PUK forces," Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman Omer
Akbel said at a news briefing here.
</P>
<P>
Reports earlier this week said that Turkish warplanes had
bombed the PUK-controlled areas and they were confirmed by Shazad
Saib, a senior official at the PUK office in Ankara.
</P>
<P>
PUK is believed to have maintained a relaxed relationship with
Turkey's outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK). Some PKK militants
reportedly took refuge in the PUK-controlled areas in northern
Iraq after Turkish troops swept their camps in the region.
</P>
<P>
Akbel said that Turkey's cross-border incursions were aimed at
wiping out the militants of PKK.
</P>
<P>
Late last month, some 15,000 Turkish troops stormed into
northern Iraq and killed more than 800 PKK militants, who are
fighting a 13-year-old war against the Turkish government for
independence in southeastern Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
