<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibia Agrees to UN Anti-Personnel Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Namibia has clarified its
position on the United Nations protocol banning landmines, Southern
African Broadcasting Association reported today.
</P>
<P>
In its statement, the Namibian Defense Ministry said Namibia had
agreed to the UN protocol on anti-personnel mines. The ministry
officials said a recent newspaper report on the govenment's position
on the ban was distorted.
</P>
<P>
The report said the Namibia Red Cross Society had approached the
defense and foreign ministries on the issue, but received
conflicting answers.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Ministry said the two government departments had the
same position regarding the ban on the use, production and stockpiling
of landmines.
</P>
<P>
The international community is to sign a global anti-personnel
landmine treaty in December in Ottawa, Canada.
</P>
<P>
Landmines have killed or maimed millions of people in areas of
military conflict such as Angola and Mozambique.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
