<DOCNO> XIE19971017.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Probing Gazprom Bond Offering in Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States is
investigating whether the Russian natural gas firm Gazprom should
be allowed to raise money in the United Sates and other financial
markets at a time when it is planning a major natural gas
investment in Iran, the State Department said today.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times reported today that the Wall Street firm
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Company is underwriting the Gazprom bond offering
-- a way that the Russian natural gas firm used to raise 1 billion
dollars, which the newspaper said "will go right into the firm's
coffers just as it is preparing to write the Iranians a fat
check."
</P>
<P>
"On the question of underwriting, our lawyers right now are
looking at the issue" of whether the bond offering violates the
Iran-Libya Sanctions Act, State Department spokesman James Foley
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 Iran-Libya Sanctions Act mandates sanctions against
companies investing more than 20 million dollars a year in Iran's
energy sector.
</P>
<P>
Underwriting is "not mentioned specifically in the ILSA
(Iran-Libya Sanctions Act) legislation but we've not made a
determination though as to whether that would be covered as among
the menu of sanctions," Foley said.
</P>
<P>
"It certainly is a risk of some kind" if Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
and Gazprom proceed with the bond offering before the U.S.
government decides if the offering violates the law, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
